| caption3          = 
| footer            = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] prime ministers [[Margaret Thatcher]] (''left'') and [[David Cameron]] (''right'') used [[Eurosceptic]] rhetoric while supporting the UK's membership and development of the [[European single market]]. Euroscepticism – and in particular the impact of the [[UK Independence Party]] (former leader [[Nigel Farage]] pictured centre) on the Conservatives' election results – contributed to Cameron's [[2015–2016 United Kingdom renegotiation of European Union membership|2015–16 attempt to renegotiate the UK's EU membership]], and ultimately the holding of the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum]].
}}

Thatcher, who had previously supported the common market and the Single European Act, in the [[Bruges speech]] of 1988 warned against "a European super-state exercising a new dominance from Brussels". She influenced [[Daniel Hannan]], who in 1990 founded the Oxford Campaign for Independent Britain; "With hindsight, some see this as the start of the campaign for Brexit", the ''[[Financial Times]]'' later wrote.<ref name="kuper20190620">{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/85fc694c-9222-11e9-b7ea-60e35ef678d2|title=How Oxford university shaped Brexit – and Britain's next prime minister|last=Kuper|first=Simon|date=20 June 2019|work=Financial Times|access-date=21 June 2019|language=en-GB|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621101919/https://www.ft.com/content/85fc694c-9222-11e9-b7ea-60e35ef678d2|archive-date=21 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The vote to approve the [[Maastricht Treaty]] in 1993 triggered a strong Eurosceptic response, splitting the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] Party and leading to many past supporters forming alternative Eurosceptic parties. This included Sir [[James Goldsmith]] forming the [[Referendum Party]] in 1994 to contest the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]] on a platform of providing a referendum on the nature of the UK's relationship with the rest of the EU.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Heath |first1=Anthony |last2=Jowell |first2=Roger |last3=Taylor |first3=Bridget |last4=Thomson |first4=Katarina |date=1 January 1998|title=Euroscepticism and the referendum party|journal=British Elections & Parties Review |volume=8 |issue=1 |pages=95–110 |doi=10.1080/13689889808413007 |issn=1368-9886}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Carter |first1=N. |last2=Evans |first2=M. |last3=Alderman |first3=K. |last4=Gorham |first4=S.|date=1 July 1998|title=Europe, Goldsmith and the Referendum Party|journal=Parliamentary Affairs |volume=51 |issue=3 |pages=470–485 |doi=10.1093/oxfordjournals.pa.a028811|issn=0031-2290}}</ref> The party fielded candidates in 547 constituencies at that election, and won 810,860 votes—2.6% of the total votes cast<ref name="ref party">{{cite web|url=http://www.politicsresources.net/area/uk/ge97/partycand.htm|title=UK Election 1997|publisher=Politicsresources.net|access-date=16 July 2015 |url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110921035222/http://www.politicsresources.net/area/uk/ge97/partycand.htm|archive-date=21 September 2011}}</ref>—but failed to win a parliamentary seat because the vote was spread across the country. The Referendum Party disbanded following Goldsmith's death in 1997.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}. The [[UK Independence Party]] (UKIP), a Eurosceptic political party, was formed in response to Maastricht in 1993. In 1997, [[Nigel Farage]] took over the leadership of the party as a right-of-centre, populist movement in [[England]].<ref>D'Arcy M. (29 November 2019) [https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2019-50565543 Nigel Farage: The story of 'Mr Brexit'] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220220081532/https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2019-50565543 |date=20 February 2022 }} BBC.com.</ref>

Prior to 2013, the issue of EU membership never scored higher than 5% on surveys of voter priorities, polling just 6% in 2013<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ipsos.com/en-uk/economistipsos-mori-january-2013-issues-index |title=Economist/Ipsos January 2013 Issues Index |publisher=Ipsos |date=22 January 2013 |access-date=21 March 2022 |archive-date=7 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220307071259/https://www.ipsos.com/en-uk/economistipsos-mori-january-2013-issues-index |url-status=live }}</ref> and 11% in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ipsos.com/en-uk/economy-immigration-and-healthcare-are-britons-top-three-issues-deciding-general-election-vote |title=Economy, immigration and healthcare are Britons' top three issues deciding general election vote |publisher=Ipsos |date=15 September 2014 |access-date=21 March 2022 |archive-date=7 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220307071247/https://www.ipsos.com/en-uk/economy-immigration-and-healthcare-are-britons-top-three-issues-deciding-general-election-vote |url-status=live }}</ref> However, an increasing proportion of voters viewed immigration and asylum as of key importance.<ref>{{cite web|title=Does Migration Cause Extreme Voting?|url=http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/fac/soc/economics/research/centres/cage/manage/publications/306-2016_becker_fetzer.pdf|work=Becker and Fetzer, University of Warwick|date=18 October 2016|access-date=30 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161114083425/http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/fac/soc/economics/research/centres/cage/manage/publications/306-2016_becker_fetzer.pdf|archive-date=14 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> By adopting a hardline anti-immigration platform and conflating the issue with EU membership, UKIP was able to achieve electoral success, reaching third place in the UK during the [[2004 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2004 European elections]], second place in the [[2009 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2009 European elections]] and first place in the [[2014 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2014 European elections]], with 27.5% of the total vote. This was the first time since the [[December 1910 United Kingdom general election|1910 general election]] that any party other than Labour or the Conservatives had taken the largest share of the vote in a nationwide election.<ref>{{cite web|title=10 key lessons from the European election results|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/may/26/10-key-lessons-european-election-results|work=The Guardian|date=26 May 2014|access-date=31 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402054604/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/may/26/10-key-lessons-european-election-results|archive-date=2 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> This electoral success and internal pressure, including from many of the remaining [[Maastricht Rebels]] within the ruling [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] party, put pressure on leader and Prime Minister [[David Cameron]], as potential voter defections to UKIP threatened defeat in the [[2015 United Kingdom general election]]. This threat was emphasised by UKIP winning two by-elections (in [[2014 Clacton by-election|Clacton]] and [[2014 Rochester and Strood by-election|Rochester and Strood]], triggered by defecting Conservative MPs) in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/ng-interactive/2015/may/07/live-uk-election-results-in-full|title=2015 UK general election results in full|author=Matt Osborn|work=The Guardian|date=7 May 2015|access-date=11 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402042953/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/ng-interactive/2015/may/07/live-uk-election-results-in-full|archive-date=2 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

=== Opinion polls 1977–2015 ===
{{Main|Opinion polling for the United Kingdom European Union membership referendum}}

Both pro- and anti-EU views had majority support at different times from 1977 to 2015.<ref name="Mortimore">{{Cite news|url=http://theconversation.com/polling-history-40-years-of-british-views-on-in-or-out-of-europe-61250|title=Polling history: 40 years of British views on "in or out" of Europe|last=Mortimore|first=Roger|newspaper=The Conversation|access-date=25 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403145856/https://theconversation.com/polling-history-40-years-of-british-views-on-in-or-out-of-europe-61250|archive-date=3 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In the [[1975 United Kingdom European Communities membership referendum|EC membership referendum of 1975]], two-thirds of British voters favoured continued EC membership. Over the decades of UK-EU membership, Euroscepticism existed on both the left and right of British politics.<ref>Gifford, Chris. ''The Making of Eurosceptic Britain''. Ashgate Publishing, 2014. pp. 55, 68</ref><ref name="Foster">Foster, Anthony. ''Euroscepticism in Contemporary British Politics: Opposition to Europe in the Conservative and Labour Parties since 1945''. Routledge, 2003. pp. 68–69</ref><ref>Taylor, Graham. ''Understanding Brexit: Why Britain Voted to Leave the European Union''. Emerald Group Publishing, 2017. p. 91. Quote: "The coalition that came together to secure Brexit, however, included a diverse range of individuals, groups and interests. [...] There were also supporters of Brexit on the left{{nbsp}}..."</ref>

According to a statistical analysis published in April 2016 by Professor [[John Curtice]] of [[Strathclyde University]], surveys showed an increase in Euroscepticism (broadly defined as a wish to leave the EU or stay in the EU and try to reduce the EU's powers) from 38% in 1993 to 65% in 2015. The BSA survey for the period of July–November 2015 showed that 60% backed the option to continue as a member and 30% backed withdrawal.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tarran|first=Brian|date=8 April 2016|title=The Economy: a Brexit vote winner?|journal=Significance|volume=13|issue=2|pages=6–7|doi=10.1111/j.1740-9713.2016.00891.x|doi-access=free}}</ref>

==Referendum of 2016==
{{Main|2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum}}

===Negotiations for membership reform===
{{Main|2015–2016 United Kingdom renegotiation of European Union membership}}

In 2012, Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] initially rejected calls for a referendum on the UK's EU membership,<ref>{{cite news|title=Cameron defies Tory right over EU referendum: Prime minister, buoyed by successful negotiations on eurozone banking reform, rejects "in or out" referendum on EU|author=Nicholas Watt|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/jun/29/cameron-no-eu-referendum|newspaper=The Guardian|date=29 June 2012|access-date=2 July 2012|quote=David Cameron placed himself on a collision course with the Tory right when he mounted a passionate defence of Britain's membership of the EU and rejected out of hand an "in or out" referendum.|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151226053945/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/jun/29/cameron-no-eu-referendum|archive-date=26 December 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> but then suggested the possibility of a future referendum to endorse his proposed renegotiation of Britain's relationship with the rest of the EU.<ref>{{cite news|title=PM accused of weak stance on Europe referendum|first=Andrew|last=Sparrow|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/jul/01/david-cameron-europe-referendum-noncommittal|newspaper=The Guardian|date=1 July 2012|access-date=2 July 2012|quote=Cameron said he would continue to work for "a different, more flexible and less onerous position for Britain within the EU".|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604094602/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/jul/01/david-cameron-europe-referendum-noncommittal|archive-date=4 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> According to the [[BBC]], "The prime minister acknowledged the need to ensure the UK's [renegotiated] position within the [EU] had 'the full-hearted support of the British people' but they needed to show 'tactical and strategic patience'."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-18659072|title=David Cameron 'prepared to consider EU referendum'|date=1 July 2012|work=BBC News|quote=Mr Cameron said{{nbsp}}... he would 'continue to work for a different, more flexible and less onerous position for Britain within the EU'.|access-date=2 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120702020639/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-18659072|archive-date=2 July 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> On 23 January 2013, under pressure from many of his MPs and from the rise of UKIP, Cameron promised in his [[Bloomberg speech]] that a Conservative government would hold an in-or-out referendum on EU membership before the end of 2017, on a renegotiated package, if elected in the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|7 May 2015 general election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-21148282|title=David Cameron promises in/out referendum on EU|work=BBC News|date=23 January 2013|access-date=23 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404020146/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-21148282|archive-date=4 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> This was included in the Conservative Party manifesto for the election.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2015-32302062|title=At-a-glance: Conservative manifesto|date=15 April 2015|work=BBC News|access-date=21 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403121018/https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2015-32302062|archive-date=3 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/apr/14/conservatives-election-manifesto-2015-the-key-points|title=Conservatives election manifesto 2015 – the key points|first=Frances|last=Perraudin|date=14 April 2015|website=The Guardian|access-date=27 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402084711/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/apr/14/conservatives-election-manifesto-2015-the-key-points|archive-date=2 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

The [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] won the election with a majority. Soon afterwards, the [[European Union Referendum Act 2015]] was introduced into [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] to enable the referendum. Cameron favoured remaining in a reformed EU, and sought to renegotiate on four key points: protection of the single market for non-eurozone countries, reduction of "red tape", exempting Britain from "ever-closer union", and restricting immigration from the rest of the EU.<ref name="BBC News Nov 2015">{{cite news|title=David Cameron sets out EU reform goals|work=BBC News|date=11 November 2015|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34770875|access-date=16 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402180734/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34770875|archive-date=2 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

In December 2015, opinion polls showed a clear majority in favour of remaining in the EU; they also showed support would drop if Cameron did not negotiate adequate safeguards{{Definition needed|What kind of 'safeguards'?|date=April 2019}} for non-eurozone member states, and restrictions on benefits for non-UK EU citizens.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://openeurope.org.uk/today/blog/new-open-europecomres-poll-failure-to-win-key-reforms-could-swing-uks-eu-referendum-vote |title=New Open Europe/ComRes poll: Failure to win key reforms could swing UK's EU referendum vote |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615190602/https://openeurope.org.uk/today/blog/new-open-europecomres-poll-failure-to-win-key-reforms-could-swing-uks-eu-referendum-vote/ |archive-date=15 June 2018 |website=openeurope.org |date=16 December 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref>

The outcome of the renegotiations was revealed in February 2016. Some limits to in-work benefits for new EU immigrants were agreed, but before they could be applied, a member state such as the UK would have to get permission from the [[European Commission]] and then from the [[European Council]], which is composed of the heads of government of every member state.<ref name="FF1">{{cite web|url=https://fullfact.org/europe/explaining-eu-deal-emergency-brake|first=Eleanore|last=Spaventa|title=Explaining the EU deal: the "emergency brake"|date=22 February 2016|access-date=25 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329183814/https://fullfact.org/europe/explaining-eu-deal-emergency-brake/|archive-date=29 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

In a speech to the House of Commons on 22 February 2016, Cameron announced a referendum date of 23 June 2016, and commented on the renegotiation settlement.<ref name="Hansard 22 February 2016 Column 21-25">{{cite web|title=Prime Minister sets out legal framework for EU withdrawal|website=UK Parliament|date=22 February 2016|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201516/cmhansrd/cm160222/debtext/160222-0001.htm#16022210000001|access-date=29 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190215050849/https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201516/cmhansrd/cm160222/debtext/160222-0001.htm#16022210000001|archive-date=15 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He spoke of an intention to trigger the Article 50 process immediately following a Leave vote and of the "two-year time period to negotiate the arrangements for exit."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/504216/The_process_for_withdrawing_from_the_EU_print_ready.pdf|title=The process for withdrawing from the European Union|publisher=Government of the United Kingdom|access-date=24 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180224014248/https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/504216/The_process_for_withdrawing_from_the_EU_print_ready.pdf|archive-date=24 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>

After the original wording for the referendum question was challenged,<ref name="Three years since the Brexit vote, meet the man behind Leave and Remain">{{cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/tyne-tees/2019-06-23/three-years-since-the-brexit-vote-meet-the-man-behind-leave-and-remain|title=Three years since the Brexit vote, meet the man behind Leave and Remain|work=ITV News|date=23 June 2019|access-date=25 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190625033043/https://www.itv.com/news/tyne-tees/2019-06-23/three-years-since-the-brexit-vote-meet-the-man-behind-leave-and-remain/|archive-date=25 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> the government agreed to change the official referendum question to "Should the United Kingdom remain a member of the European Union or leave the European Union?"

===Referendum result===
{{Main|Results of the 2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum}}

In the referendum 51.89% voted in favour of leaving the EU (Leave), and 48.11% voted in favour of remaining a member of the EU (Remain).<ref name="BBC24forecast">{{cite news|title=EU referendum: BBC forecasts UK votes to leave|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36615028|work=BBC News|access-date=24 June 2016|date=24 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724232549/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36615028|archive-date=24 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://election.news.sky.com/referendum|title=EU Referendum Results|publisher=Sky (United Kingdom)|access-date=24 June 2016|archive-url=https://archive.today/20160624063333/http://election.news.sky.com/referendum|archive-date=24 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> After this result, Cameron resigned on 13 July 2016, with [[Theresa May]] becoming Prime Minister after a [[2016 Conservative Party leadership election|leadership contest]]. A [[EU Referendum Rules triggering a 2nd EU Referendum|petition calling for a second referendum]] attracted more than four million signatures,<ref>{{cite news|first=Christopher|last=Hooton|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/brexit-petition-for-second-eu-referendum-so-popular-the-government-sites-crashing-a7099996.html|title=Brexit: Petition for second EU referendum so popular the government site's crashing|newspaper=The Independent|publisher=Independent Print Limited|date=24 June 2016|access-date=24 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726082136/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/brexit-petition-for-second-eu-referendum-so-popular-the-government-sites-crashing-a7099996.html|archive-date=26 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Adam|last=Boult|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/24/petition-for-second-eu-referendum-attracts-thousands-of-signatur/|title=Petition for second EU referendum attracts thousands of signatures|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=26 June 2016|access-date=26 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624191630/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/24/petition-for-second-eu-referendum-attracts-thousands-of-signatur/|archive-date=24 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> but was rejected by the government on 9 July.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36754376|title=Brexit: Petition for second EU referendum rejected|date=9 July 2016|work=BBC News|access-date=9 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726002830/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36754376|archive-date=26 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>
{{UKEU2016Results}}

===Voter demographics and trends===
{{further|Causes of the vote in favour of Brexit}}

A 2017 study published in the journal ''[[Economic Policy]]'' showed that the Leave vote tended to be greater in areas which had lower incomes and high [[unemployment]], a strong tradition of [[manufacturing]] employment, and in which the population had fewer [[Qualification types in the United Kingdom|qualifications]]. It also tended to be greater where there was a large flow of Eastern European migrants (mainly low-skilled workers) into areas with a large share of native low-skilled workers.<ref name="Becker-Fetzer-Novy">{{cite journal |first1=Sascha O |last1=Becker |first2=Thiemo |last2=Fetzer |first3=Dennis |last3=Novy |doi=10.1093/epolic/eix012 |title=Who voted for Brexit? A comprehensive district-level analysis |journal=Economic Policy |volume=32 |issue=92 |date= 1 October 2017 |pages= 601–650 |quote= We find that fundamental characteristics of the voting population were key drivers of the Vote Leave share, in particular, their education profiles, their historical dependence on manufacturing employment as well as low income and high unemployment. At the much finer level of wards within cities, we find that areas with deprivation in terms of education, income and employment were more likely to vote Leave. [...] A larger flow of migrants from Eastern Europe reaching a local authority area with a larger share of unqualified people or a larger share of manufacturing workers is also associated with a larger Vote Leave share|doi-access=free |hdl=10419/161877 |hdl-access=free }}</ref> Those in lower [[NRS social grade|social grades]] (especially the [[working class]]) were more likely to vote Leave, while those in higher social grades (especially the [[upper middle class]]) more likely to vote Remain.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Elise |last1=Uberoi |first2=Neil |last2=Johnston |date=25 February 2021 |url=https://researchbriefings.files.parliament.uk/documents/CBP-7501/CBP-7501.pdf |title=Political disengagement in the UK: who is disengaged? |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211008232148/https://researchbriefings.files.parliament.uk/documents/CBP-7501/CBP-7501.pdf |archive-date=8 October 2021 |url-status=live |type=Briefing paper |publisher=House of Commons Library |website=researchbriefings.files.parliament.uk |id=Number CBP-7501 |pages=25–26, 28}}</ref><ref name="Hobolt">{{cite journal|last=Hobolt|first=Sara B.|s2cid=158006844|date=20 October 2016|title=The Brexit vote: a divided nation, a divided continent|journal=Journal of European Public Policy|volume=23|issue=9|pages=1259–1277|doi=10.1080/13501763.2016.1225785|issn=1350-1763|url=http://eprints.lse.ac.uk/67546/7/Hobolt_The%20Brexit%20vote%20a%20divided%20.pdf|access-date=4 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006145434/http://eprints.lse.ac.uk/67546/7/Hobolt_The%20Brexit%20vote%20a%20divided%20.pdf|archive-date=6 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Becker|first1=Sascha O.|last2=Fetzer|first2=Thiemo|last3=Novy|first3=Dennis|date=1 October 2017|title=Who voted for Brexit? A comprehensive district-level analysis|journal=Economic Policy|volume=32|issue=92|pages=601–650|doi=10.1093/epolic/eix012|issn=0266-4658|doi-access=free|hdl=10419/161877|hdl-access=free}}</ref> Studies found that the Leave vote tended to be higher in areas affected by economic decline,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Carreras|first=Miguel|date=1 December 2019|title='What do we have to lose?': Local economic decline, prospect theory, and support for Brexit|journal=Electoral Studies|volume=62|page=102094|doi=10.1016/j.electstud.2019.102094|s2cid=211461199|issn=0261-3794}}</ref> high rates of suicides and drug-related deaths,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Koltai|first1=Jonathan|last2=Varchetta|first2=Francesco Maria|last3=McKee|first3=Martin|last4=Stuckler|first4=David|title=Deaths of Despair and Brexit Votes: Cross-Local Authority Statistical Analysis in England and Wales|journal=American Journal of Public Health|volume=110|issue=3|pages=e1–e6|doi=10.2105/AJPH.2019.305488|pmid=31855481|issn=0090-0036|year=2020|pmc=7002930}}</ref> and [[austerity]] reforms introduced in 2010.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Fetzer|first=Thiemo|date=2019|title=Did Austerity Cause Brexit?|journal=American Economic Review|volume=109|issue=11|pages=3849–3886|doi=10.1257/aer.20181164|issn=0002-8282|doi-access=free|hdl=10419/181359|hdl-access=free}}</ref>

Studies suggest that older people were more likely to vote Leave, and younger people more likely to vote Remain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcthree/article/b8d097b0-3ad4-4dd9-aa25-af6374292de0|title=The truth about young people and Brexit|last=Spratt|first=Vicky|date=26 September 2018|publisher=BBC Three|language=en-GB|access-date=4 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191125041738/https://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcthree/article/b8d097b0-3ad4-4dd9-aa25-af6374292de0|archive-date=25 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> According to Thomas Sampson, an economist at the [[London School of Economics]], "Older and less-educated voters were more likely to vote 'leave' [...] A majority of white voters wanted to leave, but only 33% of Asian voters and 27% of black voters chose leave. [...] Leaving the European Union received support from across the political spectrum [...] Voting to leave the European Union was strongly associated with holding socially conservative political beliefs, opposing cosmopolitanism, and thinking life in Britain is getting worse."<ref name="Sampson-2017">{{Cite journal|last=Sampson|first=Thomas|s2cid=158102705|year=2017|title=Brexit: The Economics of International Disintegration|url=http://cep.lse.ac.uk/pubs/download/dp1499.pdf|journal=Journal of Economic Perspectives|volume=31|issue=4|pages=163–184|doi=10.1257/jep.31.4.163|issn=0895-3309|quote=The results I summarize in this section focus on long-run effects and have a forecast horizon of 10 or more years after Brexit occurs. Less is known about the likely dynamics of the transition process or the extent to which economic uncertainty and anticipation effects will impact the economies of the United Kingdom or the European Union in advance of Brexit.|access-date=20 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214033313/http://cep.lse.ac.uk/pubs/download/dp1499.pdf|archive-date=14 December 2019|url-status=live|doi-access=free}}</ref>

Polling conducted by YouGov supported these conclusions, showing that factors such as age, political party affiliation, education, and household income were the primary factors indicating how people would vote. For example, Conservative Party voters were 61% likely to vote leave, compared to Labour Party voters, who were 35% likely to vote leave. Age was one of the biggest factors affecting whether someone would vote leave, with 64% of people over the age of 65 likely to vote leave, whereas 18–24-year-olds were only 29% likely to vote leave. Education was another factor indicating voting likelihood: people with a [[GCSE]] or lower level of education were 70% likely to vote leave, whereas university graduates were only 32% likely to vote leave. Household income was another important factor, with households earning less than £20,000 62% likely to vote leave, compared to households earning £60,000 or more, which were only 35% likely to vote leave.<ref>{{Cite web|date=27 June 2016|last=Moore|first=Peter|website=[[YouGov]]|title=How Britain Voted at the EU referendum|url=https://yougov.co.uk/topics/politics/articles-reports/2016/06/27/how-britain-voted|url-status=live|archive-date=2 September 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210902093901/https://yougov.co.uk/topics/politics/articles-reports/2016/06/27/how-britain-voted}}</ref>

There were major variations in geographic support for each side. Scotland and Northern Ireland both returned majorities for remain, although these had a relatively small impact on the overall result as England has a much larger population. There were also significant regional differences within England, with most of London returning a majority remain vote, alongside urban centres in northern England such as Manchester and Liverpool, which returned remain majorities of 60% and 58% respectively. Opposite trends appeared in industrial and [[Post-industrial economy|post-industrial]] areas of [[Northern England]], with areas such as North Lincolnshire and South Tyneside both heavily supporting leave.<ref>{{Cite web|date=2016|title=EU Referendum results|website=bbc.co.uk|publisher=BBC|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/eu_referendum/results|url-status=live|archive-date=4 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210304094326/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/eu_referendum/results}}</ref>

Opinion polls found that Leave voters believed leaving the EU was "more likely to bring about a better immigration system, improved border controls, a fairer welfare system, better quality of life, and the ability to control our own laws", while Remain voters believed EU membership "would be better for the economy, international investment, and the UK's influence in the world." Polls found that the main reasons people voted Leave were "the principle that decisions about the UK should be taken in the UK", and that leaving "offered the best chance for the UK to regain control over immigration and its own borders." The main reason people voted Remain was that "the risks of voting to leave the EU looked too great when it came to things like the economy, jobs and prices."<ref>[http://lordashcroftpolls.com/2016/06/how-the-united-kingdom-voted-and-why/ "How the United Kingdom voted on Thursday{{nbsp}}... and why"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401203252/http://lordashcroftpolls.com/2016/06/how-the-united-kingdom-voted-and-why/ |date=1 April 2019 }}. Lord Ashcroft Polls. 24 June 2016.</ref>

===Post-referendum investigations===
{{see also|1=2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum#Investigations into campaigns|2=Allegations of unlawful campaigning in the 2016 EU referendum|label1=European Union membership referendum § Investigations into campaigns}}
Following the referendum, a series of irregularities related to campaign spending were investigated by the [[Electoral Commission (United Kingdom)|Electoral Commission]], which subsequently issued a large number of fines. In February 2017, the main campaign group for the "Leave" vote, [[Leave.EU]], was fined £50,000 for sending marketing messages without permission.<ref>{{cite web |title=EU campaign firm fined for sending spam texts |url=https://ico.org.uk/about-the-ico/news-and-events/news-and-blogs/2016/05/eu-campaign-firm-fined-for-sending-spam-texts/ |publisher=Information Commissioner's Office |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170705124856/https://ico.org.uk/about-the-ico/news-and-events/news-and-blogs/2016/05/eu-campaign-firm-fined-for-sending-spam-texts/ |archive-date=5 July 2017 |date=11 May 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref> In December 2017, the [[Electoral Commission (United Kingdom)|Electoral Commission]] fined two pro-EU groups, the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] (£18,000) and [[Open Britain]] (£1,250), for breaches of campaign finance rules during the referendum campaign.<ref>{{cite news |last=Maidment |first=Jack |date=19 December 2017 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/12/19/liberal-democrats-fined-18000-breaching-campaign-finance-rules |title=Liberal Democrats fined £18,000 for breaching campaign finance rules relating to EU referendum |work=The Daily Telegraph |access-date=10 July 2021 |archive-date=12 July 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210712015216/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/12/19/liberal-democrats-fined-18000-breaching-campaign-finance-rules/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In May 2018, the Electoral Commission fined Leave.EU £70,000 for unlawfully overspending and inaccurately reporting loans from [[Arron Banks]] totalling £6&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/may/11/leaveeu-fined-70k-breaches-of-electoral-law-eu-referendum|title=Leave.EU fined £70k over breaches of electoral law|last=Weaver|first=Matthew|date=11 May 2018|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=11 May 2018|archive-date=13 July 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230713184737/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/may/11/leaveeu-fined-70k-breaches-of-electoral-law-eu-referendum|url-status=live}}</ref> Smaller fines were levelled against the pro-EU campaign group Best for Our Future and two trade union donors for inaccurate reporting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/i-am-a/journalist/electoral-commission-media-centre/news-releases-donations/campaigners-and-political-parties-fined-for-breaching-political-finance-rules |title=Campaigners and political parties fined for breaching political finance rules |website=The Electoral Commission |date=15 May 2018 |archive-date=1 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401213339/https://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/i-am-a/journalist/electoral-commission-media-centre/party-and-election-finance-to-keep/campaigners-and-political-parties-fined-for-breaching-political-finance-rules |url-status=dead}}</ref> In July 2018 [[Vote Leave]] was fined £61,000 for overspending, not declaring finances shared with [[BeLeave]], and failing to comply with investigators.<ref>[https://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/i-am-a/journalist/electoral-commission-media-centre/party-and-election-finance-to-keep/vote-leave-fined-and-referred-to-the-police-for-breaking-electoral-law "Vote Leave fined and referred to the police for breaking electoral law"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729202449/https://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/i-am-a/journalist/electoral-commission-media-centre/party-and-election-finance-to-keep/vote-leave-fined-and-referred-to-the-police-for-breaking-electoral-law |date=29 July 2019 }}. The Electoral Commission. 17 July 2018</ref>

In November 2017, the Electoral Commission launched a probe into [[Russian interference in the 2016 Brexit referendum|claims that Russia had attempted to sway public opinion]] over the referendum using social media platforms such as Twitter and Facebook.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gillett |first1=Francesca |title=Electoral Commission launches probe into Russian meddling in Brexit vote using Twitter and Facebook |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/election-watchdog-launches-probe-into-russian-meddling-in-brexit-vote-a3674251.html |work=Evening Standard |access-date=29 April 2021 |archive-date=23 April 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210423084321/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/election-watchdog-launches-probe-into-russian-meddling-in-brexit-vote-a3674251.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

In February 2019, the parliamentary [[Digital, Culture, Media and Sport Committee]] called for an inquiry into "foreign influence, disinformation, funding, voter manipulation, and the sharing of data" in the Brexit vote.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-vote-investigate-law-breaking-influence-manipulation-theresa-may-facebook-a8783746.html |title=Theresa May must investigate 'foreign influence and voter manipulation' in Brexit vote, say MPs |date=18 February 2019 |newspaper=The Independent |access-date=18 February 2019 |archive-date=18 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218032423/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-vote-investigate-law-breaking-influence-manipulation-theresa-may-facebook-a8783746.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

In July 2020, [[Intelligence and Security Committee of Parliament]] published a [[Intelligence and Security Committee Russia report|report]] which accused the UK government of actively avoiding investigating whether Russia interfered with public opinion. The report did not pass judgement over whether Russian information operations had an impact on the result.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Ellehuus |first1=Rachel |title=Did Russia Influence Brexit? |url=https://www.csis.org/blogs/brexit-bits-bobs-and-blogs/did-russia-influence-brexit |website=Center for Strategic and International Studies |access-date=29 April 2021 |archive-date=1 May 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210501075748/https://www.csis.org/blogs/brexit-bits-bobs-and-blogs/did-russia-influence-brexit |url-status=live }}</ref>

==Withdrawal process==
{{Further|Withdrawal from the European Union}}{{wikisource|Consolidated version of the Treaty on European Union/Title VI: Final Provisions#Article 50|Article 50 of the Treaty on European Union}}Withdrawal from the European Union is governed by Article 50 of the [[Treaty on European Union]]. It was originally drafted by [[Lord Kerr of Kinlochard]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/article-50-design-dictators-not-uk-eu-european-lisbon-treaty-author-lord-kerr-a7655891.html|title=Article 50 was designed for European dictators, not the UK, says man who wrote it|last=Kentish|first=Benjamin|date=29 March 2017|work=The Independent|access-date=29 December 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229205359/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/article-50-design-dictators-not-uk-eu-european-lisbon-treaty-author-lord-kerr-a7655891.html|archive-date=29 December 2019}}</ref> and introduced by the [[Treaty of Lisbon]] which entered into force in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-37852628|title=Article 50 author Lord Kerr says Brexit not inevitable|work=BBC News|date=3 November 2016|quote=After leaving the foreign office, he was secretary-general of the European [C]onvention, which drafted what became the Lisbon treaty. It included Article 50 which sets out the process by which any member state can leave the EU.|access-date=20 June 2018|archive-date=25 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180325154559/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-37852628|url-status=live}}</ref> The article states that any member state can withdraw "in accordance with its own constitutional requirements" by notifying the [[European Council]] of its intention to do so.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rankin|first1=Jennifer|last2=Borger|first2=Julian|last3=Rice-Oxley|first3=Mark|title=What is article 50 and why is it so central to the Brexit debate?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/25/article-50-brexit-debate-britain-eu|url-status=live|work=The Guardian|date=25 June 2016|access-date=29 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229105344/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/25/article-50-brexit-debate-britain-eu|archive-date=29 December 2019}}</ref> The notification triggers a two-year negotiation period, in which the EU must "negotiate and conclude an agreement with [the leaving] State, setting out the arrangements for its withdrawal, taking account of the framework for its future relationship with the [European] Union".<ref name="constunit" /> If no agreement is reached within the two years, the membership ends without an agreement, unless an extension is unanimously agreed among all EU states, including the withdrawing state.<ref name="constunit" /> On the EU side, the agreement needs to be ratified by [[Voting in the Council of the European Union|qualified majority in the European Council]], and by the European Parliament.<ref name="constunit" />

===Invocation of Article 50===
{{Main|United Kingdom invocation of Article 50 of the Treaty on European Union}}
[[File:Prime Minister’s letter to Donald Tusk triggering Article 50.pdf|thumb|upright|Letter from Theresa May invoking Article 50]]The 2015 Referendum Act did not expressly require Article 50 to be invoked,<ref name="constunit">{{cite web|url=https://constitution-unit.com/2016/01/19/what-happens-if-we-vote-for-brexit/|title=What happens if we vote for Brexit?|last=Renwick|first=Alan|date=19 January 2016|website=The Constitution Unit Blog|access-date=14 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731162921/https://constitution-unit.com/2016/01/19/what-happens-if-we-vote-for-brexit/|archive-date=31 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> but prior to the referendum, the British government said it would respect the result.<ref>In [[EU leaflet|a leaflet]] sent out before the referendum, the UK government stated "This is your decision. The Government will implement what you decide." {{Cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/515068/why-the-government-believes-that-voting-to-remain-in-the-european-union-is-the-best-decision-for-the-uk.pdf|title=Why the Government believes that voting to remain in the European Union is the best decision for the UK. The EU referendum, Thursday, 23 June 2016.|access-date=28 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180324214934/https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/515068/why-the-government-believes-that-voting-to-remain-in-the-european-union-is-the-best-decision-for-the-uk.pdf|archive-date=24 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> When Cameron resigned following the referendum, he said that it would be for the incoming prime minister to invoke Article 50.<ref name=cameronquit>{{cite news|access-date=24 June 2016|work=BBC News|date=24 June 2016|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36615028|title=Brexit: David Cameron to quit after UK votes to leave EU|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724232549/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36615028|archive-date=24 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Cooper|first=Charlie|date=27 June 2016|title=David Cameron rules out second EU referendum after Brexit|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-what-is-eu-referendum-petition-david-cameron-a7105596.html|newspaper=The Independent|location=London|access-date=27 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190616105002/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-what-is-eu-referendum-petition-david-cameron-a7105596.html|archive-date=16 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The new prime minister, [[Theresa May]], said she would wait until 2017 to invoke the article, in order to prepare for the negotiations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/20/angela-merkel-backs-theresa-mays-plan-not-to-trigger-brexit-this-year|title=Angela Merkel backs Theresa May's plan not to trigger Brexit this year|last1=Mason|first1=Rowena|date=20 July 2016|work=The Guardian|access-date=29 December 2019|url-status=live|last2=Oltermann|first2=Philip|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160720232931/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/20/angela-merkel-backs-theresa-mays-plan-not-to-trigger-brexit-this-year|archive-date=20 July 2016}}</ref> In October 2016, she said Britain would trigger Article 50 in March 2017,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/theresa-may-to-begin-brexit-process-by-end-of-march/|title=Theresa May to begin Brexit process by end of March|last=Spence|first=Alex|date=2 October 2016|work=Politico|access-date=29 December 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229190204/https://www.politico.eu/article/theresa-may-to-begin-brexit-process-by-end-of-march/|archive-date=29 December 2019}}</ref> and in December she gained the support of MP's for her timetable.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/british-mps-back-theresa-mays-brexit-timetable/|title=British MPs back Theresa May's Brexit timetable|last=Cooper|first=Charlie|date=9 December 2016|work=Politico|access-date=29 December 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229190203/https://www.politico.eu/article/british-mps-back-theresa-mays-brexit-timetable/|archive-date=29 December 2019}}</ref>

In January 2017, the [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]] ruled in [[R (Miller and Dos Santos) v Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union|the Miller case]] that government could only invoke Article 50 if authorised by an act of parliament to do so.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bowcott|first1=Owen|last2=Mason|first2=Rowena|last3=Asthana|first3=Anushka|title=Supreme court rules parliament must have vote to trigger article 50|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jan/24/supreme-court-brexit-ruling-parliament-vote-article-50|access-date=9 February 2017|newspaper=The Guardian|date=24 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190527033524/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jan/24/supreme-court-brexit-ruling-parliament-vote-article-50|archive-date=27 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The government subsequently introduced a bill for that purpose, and it was passed into law on 16 March as the [[European Union (Notification of Withdrawal) Act 2017]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/03/16/queen-give-royal-assent-article-50-bill-clearing-way-theresa/|title=Queen gives royal assent to Article 50 Bill, clearing way for Theresa May to start European Union exit talks|date=16 March 2017|work=The Telegraph|access-date=29 December 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229192010/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/03/16/queen-give-royal-assent-article-50-bill-clearing-way-theresa/|archive-date=29 December 2019}}</ref> On 29 March, [[Theresa May]] triggered Article 50 when [[Tim Barrow]], the British ambassador to the EU, delivered the invocation letter to European Council President [[Donald Tusk]]. This made 29 March 2019 the expected date that UK would leave EU.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39422353|title=Article 50: UK set to formally trigger Brexit process|date=29 March 2017|work=BBC|access-date=29 December 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727021653/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39422353|archive-date=27 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39431428|title='No turning back' on Brexit as Article 50 triggered|date=30 March 2017|work=BBC News|access-date=29 December 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727023251/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39431428|archive-date=27 July 2019}}</ref>

===2017 UK general election===
{{see also|2017 United Kingdom general election}}

[[File:2017UKElectionMap.svg|thumb|upright=1.35|right|A map presenting the results of the 2017 United Kingdom general election, by party of the MP elected from each constituency, with Conservatives in blue, Labour in red, and SNP in yellow]]

In April 2017, [[Theresa May]] called a [[2017 United Kingdom general election|snap general election, held on 8 June]], in an attempt to "strengthen [her] hand" in the negotiations;<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/after-british-vote-brexit-negotiations-could-be-delayed/2017/06/09/1a2fee88-4c9b-11e7-987c-42ab5745db2e_story.html|title=After shocking British vote result, Europe ponders fate of Brexit negotiations|last=McAuley|first=James|date=9 June 2017|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=29 December 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229230200/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/after-british-vote-brexit-negotiations-could-be-delayed/2017/06/09/1a2fee88-4c9b-11e7-987c-42ab5745db2e_story.html|archive-date=29 December 2019}}</ref> The Conservative Party, Labour and UKIP made manifesto pledges to implement the referendum, the Labour manifesto differing in its approach to Brexit negotiations, such as unilaterally offering permanent residence to EU immigrants.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Asthana|first1=Anushka|last2=Walker |first2=Peter|title=Theresa May calls for general election to secure Brexit mandate |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/apr/18/theresa-may-calls-for-general-election-in-bid-to-secure-brexit-mandate|access-date=19 April 2017|work=The Guardian|date=19 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712181222/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/apr/18/theresa-may-calls-for-general-election-in-bid-to-secure-brexit-mandate|archive-date=12 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39742407|title=General election 2017: UKIP needed to stop Brexit 'backsliding'|date=28 April 2017|work=BBC News|access-date=29 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727070503/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39742407|archive-date=27 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39698465|title=General Election 2017: Labour's 'day one' pledge to EU nationals|date=25 April 2017|work=BBC News|access-date=25 April 2017 |url-status=live|archive-date=27 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727061457/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39698465}}</ref> The Liberal Democrat Party and the [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] manifestos proposed a policy of remaining in the EU via a [[Proposed referendum on the Brexit withdrawal agreement|second referendum]].<ref>{{cite news|title='This is your chance,' Lib Dems tell voters opposed to Hard Brexit |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/15230750._This_is_your_chance___Lib_Dems_tell_voters_opposed_to_Hard_Brexit/|access-date=23 April 2017|work=The Herald|date=18 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825114208/http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/15230750._This_is_your_chance___Lib_Dems_tell_voters_opposed_to_Hard_Brexit/|archive-date=25 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-second-eu-referendum-green-party-caroline-lucas-leader-elected-a7222221.html|title=Green Party leader Caroline Lucas calls for second EU referendum|date=2 September 2016 |work=The Independent|access-date=19 April 2017|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190612060902/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-second-eu-referendum-green-party-caroline-lucas-leader-elected-a7222221.html|archive-date=12 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tim-farron-general-election-liberal-democrat-leader-snap-change-country-direction-chance-june-8-a7688486.html|title=Lib Dem leader Tim Farron responds to Theresa May's general election announcement|date=18 April 2017|work=The Independent|access-date=19 April 2017|url-status=live|archive-date=5 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190705211044/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tim-farron-general-election-liberal-democrat-leader-snap-change-country-direction-chance-june-8-a7688486.html}}</ref> The Scottish National Party (SNP) manifesto proposed a policy of waiting for the outcome of the Brexit negotiations and then holding a referendum on [[Scottish independence]].<ref>{{cite web|date=1 June 2017 |url=https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/thesnp/pages/9544/attachments/original/1496320559/Manifesto_06_01_17.pdf?1496320559|title=Stronger for Scotland|access-date=13 June 2018|publisher=SNP website|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609083758/https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/thesnp/pages/9544/attachments/original/1496320559/Manifesto_06_01_17.pdf?1496320559|archive-date=9 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2017-40091999|title=SNP manifesto summary: Key points at-a-glance|work=BBC News|date=30 May 2017|access-date=13 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206031824/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2017-40091999|archive-date=6 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>

The result produced an unexpected [[hung parliament]], the governing Conservatives gained votes and remained the largest party but nevertheless lost seats and their majority in the House of Commons. Labour gained significantly on votes and seats, retaining its position as the second-largest party. The Liberal Democrats gained six seats despite a slight decrease in vote share compared with 2015. The Green Party kept its single MP while also losing national vote share. Losing votes and seats were the SNP, which lost 21 MPs, and UKIP, which suffered a −10.8% swing and lost its only MP. The [[Democratic Unionist Party]] (DUP) and [[Sinn Féin]] also made gains in votes and seats.<ref>{{cite news|title=Election 2017 Results|work=BBC News|date=9 June 2017 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election/2017/results|access-date=13 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531172514/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election/2017/results |archive-date=31 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 26 June 2017, Conservatives and the DUP reached a [[confidence and supply]] agreement whereby the DUP would back the Conservatives in key votes in the House of Commons over the course of the parliament. The agreement included additional funding of £1&nbsp;billion for Northern Ireland, highlighted mutual support for Brexit and national security, expressed commitment to the Good Friday Agreement, and indicated that policies such as the state pension triple lock and [[Winter Fuel Payment]]s would be maintained.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-40403434|title=Conservatives agree pact with DUP to support May government|date=26 June 2017|work=BBC News |access-date=26 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190728173408/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-40403434|archive-date=28 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2017-40245514|title=Theresa May and the DUP deal: What you need to know|last=Hunt|first=Alex|date=26 June 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=30 December 2019|url-status=live|archive-date=26 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626230416/https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2017-40245514}}</ref>

===UK–EU negotiations in 2017 and 2018===
{{Main|Brexit negotiations}}

Prior to the negotiations, May said that the British government would not seek permanent [[Membership of the United Kingdom in the European Economic Area|single market membership]], would end ECJ jurisdiction, seek a new trade agreement, end [[free movement of people]] and maintain the [[Common Travel Area]] with [[Ireland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/the-governments-negotiating-objectives-for-exiting-the-eu-pm-speech|title=The government's negotiating objectives for exiting the EU: PM speech|date=17 January 2017|publisher=Gov.uk|access-date=24 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170122234703/https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/the-governments-negotiating-objectives-for-exiting-the-eu-pm-speech|archive-date=22 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The EU had adopted its [[European Union negotiating directives for Brexit|negotiating directives]] in May,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2017/05/22-brexit-negotiating-directives/|title=Council (Art 50) authorises the start of Brexit talks and adopts negotiating directives – Consilium|publisher=Europa (web portal)|access-date=23 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170928145943/http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2017/05/22-brexit-negotiating-directives/|archive-date=28 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and appointed [[Michel Barnier]] as Chief Negotiator.<ref name="Guardian-uk-caves" /> The EU wished to perform the negotiations in two phases: first the UK would agree to a financial commitment and to lifelong benefits for EU citizens in Britain, and then negotiations on a future relationship could begin.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/04/29/eu-brexit-guidelines-document-really-means/|title=EU Brexit guidelines: What's in the document, and what it really means|last=Foster|first=Peter|date=29 April 2017|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=14 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402033538/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/04/29/eu-brexit-guidelines-document-really-means/|archive-date=2 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In the first phase, the member states would demand that the UK pay a "[[Brexit divorce bill|divorce bill]]", initially estimated as amounting to £52&nbsp;billion.<ref>"Divorce settlement or leaving the club? A breakdown of the Brexit bill" March 2017, [http://bruegel.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/WP_2017_03-.pdf A breakdown of the Brexit bill (2017)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709094307/http://bruegel.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/WP_2017_03-.pdf |date=9 July 2018 }}</ref> EU negotiators said that an agreement must be reached between UK and the EU by October 2018.<ref name="brexitoct18">{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/business/articles/2017-09-22/the-latest-protests-in-florence-as-uk-leader-may-speaks|title=The Latest: EU's Brexit Chief Welcomes 'Constructive' Speech|website=USNews.com|access-date=1 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330233432/https://www.usnews.com/news/business/articles/2017-09-22/the-latest-protests-in-florence-as-uk-leader-may-speaks|archive-date=30 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

Negotiations commenced on 19 June 2017.<ref name="Guardian-uk-caves">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jun/19/uk-caves-in-to-eu-demand-to-agree-divorce-bill-before-trade-talks|title=Brexit: UK caves in to EU demand to agree divorce bill before trade talks|last=Roberts|first=Dan|date=20 June 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=9 September 2017|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620101013/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jun/19/uk-caves-in-to-eu-demand-to-agree-divorce-bill-before-trade-talks|archive-date=20 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Negotiating groups were established for three topics: the rights of EU citizens living in Britain and vice versa; Britain's outstanding financial obligations to the EU; and the border between Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/sites/beta-political/files/eu-uk-art-50-terms-reference_agreed_amends_en.pdf|title=Terms of Reference for the Article 50 TEU negotiations|date=19 June 2017|website=European Commission|access-date=29 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829213212/https://ec.europa.eu/commission/sites/beta-political/files/eu-uk-art-50-terms-reference_agreed_amends_en.pdf|archive-date=29 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/research-briefings/cbp-8017/ |title=Brexit: the talks begin |publisher=House of Commons Library |website=commonslibrary.parliament.uk |date=12 July 2017 |type=Research briefing |last1=Lang |first1=Arabella |last2=Curtis |first2=John |last3=Walker |first3=Nigel |last4=Keen |first4=Richard |last5=Hinson |first5=Suzanna |last6=McGuinness |first6=Terry |last7=Miller |first7=Vaughne |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211121150324/https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/research-briefings/cbp-8017/ |archive-date=21 November 2021 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/britain/2017/06/22/let-the-brussels-games-begin|title=Let the Brussels games begin|access-date=22 September 2018|publisher=Economist.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923052143/https://www.economist.com/britain/2017/06/22/let-the-brussels-games-begin|archive-date=23 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In December 2017, a partial agreement was reached. It ensured that there would be no hard border in Ireland, protected the rights of UK citizens in the EU and of EU citizens in Britain, and estimated the financial settlement to be £35–39&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/uk/brexit-breakthrough-may-pledges-no-hard-border-as-commission-says-sufficient-progress-made-1.3320030|title=Brexit breakthrough: May pledges 'no hard border' as commission says 'sufficient progress' made|newspaper=[[The Irish Times]]|date=8 December 2017|access-date=8 December 2017|archive-date=10 April 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240410051731/https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/uk/brexit-breakthrough-may-pledges-no-hard-border-as-commission-says-sufficient-progress-made-1.3320030|url-status=live}}</ref> May stressed that "Nothing is agreed until everything is agreed".<ref>{{cite news |last=Hope |first=Christopher |author-link=Christopher Hope (journalist) |title=Theresa May to tell Ireland 'nothing is agreed' on terms of Brexit as row over deal intensifies |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/12/11/theresa-may-tell-ireland-nothing-agreed-terms-brexit-row-deal/ |url-status=live |work=The Telegraph |date=11 December 2017 |access-date=18 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017235503/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/12/11/theresa-may-tell-ireland-nothing-agreed-terms-brexit-row-deal/ |archive-date=17 October 2019}}</ref> Following this partial agreement, EU leaders agreed to move on to the second phase in the negotiations: discussion of the future relationship, a transition period and a possible trade deal.<ref>{{cite news |last=Boffey |first=Daniel|title=EU leaders agree Brexit talks can move on to phase two|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/dec/15/brexit-talks-eu-next-phase-brussels-theresa-may|date=15 December 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=18 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017235504/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/dec/15/brexit-talks-eu-next-phase-brussels-theresa-may|archive-date=17 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

In March 2018, a 21-month transition period and the terms for it were provisionally agreed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/19/world/europe/uk-brexit-eu.html|title=U.K. Reaches Brexit Transition Deal With E.U.|last=Castle|first=Stephen|date=19 March 2018|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=30 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629160826/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/19/world/europe/uk-brexit-eu.html|archive-date=29 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In June 2018, Irish [[Taoiseach]] [[Leo Varadkar]] said that there had been little progress on the [[Irish border question]]{{mdash}}on which the EU proposed a [[Irish backstop|backstop]], to come into effect if no overall trade deal had been reached by the end of the transition period{{mdash}}and that it was unlikely that there would be a solution before October, when the whole deal was to be agreed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/border-deal-is-not-likely-until-october-taoiseach-claims-1.3525988|title=Border deal is not likely until October, Taoiseach claims |date=11 June 2018|newspaper=The Irish Times|access-date=11 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180711032020/https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/border-deal-is-not-likely-until-october-taoiseach-claims-1.3525988|archive-date=11 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In July 2018, the British government published the [[Chequers plan]], containing its aims for the future relationship that was to be determined in the negotiations. The plan sought to keep British access to the single market for goods, but not necessarily for services, while allowing for an independent [[trade policy]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Carswell |first=Simon |title=Brexit explained: What is Theresa May's Chequers plan?|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/uk/brexit-explained-what-is-theresa-may-s-chequers-plan-1.3661485|date=12 October 2018|newspaper=The Irish Times|access-date=18 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815075412/https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/uk/brexit-explained-what-is-theresa-may-s-chequers-plan-1.3661485|archive-date=15 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The plan caused cabinet resignations, including those of [[Brexit Secretary]] [[David Davis (British politician)|David Davis]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jul/08/david-davis-resigns-as-brexit-secretary-reports-say|title=Brexit secretary David Davis resigns plunging government into crisis|last=Stewart|first=Heather|date=9 July 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=1 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731123700/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jul/08/david-davis-resigns-as-brexit-secretary-reports-say|archive-date=31 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Foreign Secretary]] [[Boris Johnson]].<ref name="S,C,S">{{cite news |last1=Stewart |first1=Heather |last2=Crerar |first2=Pippa |last3=Sabbagh |first3=Dan|title=May's plan 'sticks in the throat', says Boris Johnson as he resigns over Brexit|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jul/09/boris-johnson-resigns-as-foreign-secretary-brexit|work=The Guardian|date=9 July 2018|access-date=31 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831034544/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jul/09/boris-johnson-resigns-as-foreign-secretary-brexit|archive-date=31 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>

===May's agreement and failed ratification===
{{main|Brexit withdrawal agreement|Parliamentary votes on Brexit}}
{{Wikisource|Draft Agreement on the Withdrawal of the United Kingdom from the European Union|2018 Draft withdrawal agreement}}
On 13 November 2018, UK and EU negotiators agreed the text of a draft withdrawal agreement,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cooper |first1=Charlie |last2=Bayer |first2=Lili |last3=Barigazzi |first3=Jacopo |title=Theresa May calls Cabinet meeting to approve Brexit 'draft agreement' |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/uk-cabinet-meeting-wednesday-to-consider-brexit-technical-agreement/ |url-status=live |work=Politico |date=14 November 2018 |access-date=30 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230185457/https://www.politico.eu/article/uk-cabinet-meeting-wednesday-to-consider-brexit-technical-agreement/ |archive-date=30 December 2019}}</ref> and May secured her Cabinet's backing of the deal the following day,<ref>{{cite news|title=Brexit: Cabinet backs draft agreement|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-46215930|date=14 November 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=15 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190419181835/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-46215930|archive-date=19 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> though Brexit Secretary [[Dominic Raab]] resigned over "fatal flaws" in the agreement.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-46219495|title=Brexit: Dominic Raab and Esther McVey among ministers to quit over EU agreement|date=15 November 2018|access-date=15 November 2018|work=BBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617094908/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-46219495|archive-date=17 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It was expected that ratification in the British parliament would be difficult.<ref name="BBC News-2019">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-46334649|title=EU leaders agree UK's Brexit deal at Brussels summit|date=25 November 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=30 December 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190910162614/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-46334649|archive-date=10 September 2019}}</ref><ref name="Cook-2018">{{cite news|last1=Cook|first1=Lorne|last2=Lawless|first2=Jill|last3=Casert|first3=Raf|url=https://apnews.com/e1384dc86bcd418a9eeddd81fdb27f78|title=EU seals Brexit deal as May faces a hard sell at home|date=25 November 2018|work=Associated Press|access-date=30 December 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230185501/https://apnews.com/e1384dc86bcd418a9eeddd81fdb27f78|archive-date=30 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/nov/25/theresa-may-not-sad-but-defiant-makes-case-for-brexit-deal|title=Not sad but defiant: Theresa May makes case for Brexit deal|last=Stewart|first=Heather|date=25 November 2018|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230185458/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/nov/25/theresa-may-not-sad-but-defiant-makes-case-for-brexit-deal|archive-date=30 December 2019|access-date=30 December 2019}}</ref> On 25 November, all 27 leaders of the remaining EU countries endorsed the agreement.<ref name="BBC News-2019" /><ref name="Cook-2018" />

On 10 December 2018, the Prime Minister postponed the vote in the House of Commons on her Brexit deal. This came minutes after the [[Prime Minister's Office (United Kingdom)|Prime Minister's Office]] confirmed the vote would be going ahead.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-vote-delayed-postponed-theresa-may-commons-parliament-date-time-eu-deal-cabinet-a8675906.html|title=Theresa May calls off vote on Brexit deal after massive opposition from Tory rebels|date=10 December 2018|website=The Independent|access-date=11 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190619210106/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-vote-delayed-postponed-theresa-may-commons-parliament-date-time-eu-deal-cabinet-a8675906.html|archive-date=19 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Faced with the prospect of a defeat in the House of Commons, this option gave May more time to negotiate with Conservative [[backbencher]]s and the EU, even though they had ruled out further discussions.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/dec/10/eu-figures-rule-out-concessions-as-theresa-may-postpones-brexit-vote|title=EU figures rule out concessions as May postpones Brexit vote|last=Boffey|first=Daniels|date=10 December 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=29 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190522111207/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/dec/10/eu-figures-rule-out-concessions-as-theresa-may-postpones-brexit-vote|archive-date=22 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The decision was met with calls from many [[Welsh Labour]] MPs for a [[Motions of no confidence in the United Kingdom|motion of no confidence]] in the Government.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2018-12-11/welsh-labour-mps-call-for-no-confidence-vote/|title=Welsh Labour MPs call for no confidence vote|website=ITV News|access-date=11 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708151738/https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2018-12-11/welsh-labour-mps-call-for-no-confidence-vote/|archive-date=8 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

Also on 10 December 2018, the [[European Court of Justice]] (ECJ) ruled that the UK could unilaterally revoke its notification of withdrawal, as long as it was still a member and had not agreed a withdrawal agreement. The decision to do so should be "unequivocal and unconditional" and "follow a democratic process".<ref>{{cite news|date=10 December 2018|title=Brexit ruling: UK can cancel decision, EU court says|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-46481643|url-status=live|access-date=29 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103035740/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-46481643|archive-date=3 January 2020}}</ref> If the British revoked their notification, they would remain a member of the EU under their current membership terms. The case was launched by Scottish politicians and referred to the ECJ by the Scottish [[Court of Session]].<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Taylor|first1=Robert|last2=Wilson|first2=Adelyn|date=11 December 2018|title=Revoking Article 50 after the ECJ's ruling|work=The UK in a Changing Europe|url=https://ukandeu.ac.uk/revoking-article-50-after-the-ecjs-ruling/|url-status=live|access-date=29 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190710143108/https://ukandeu.ac.uk/revoking-article-50-after-the-ecjs-ruling/|archive-date=10 July 2019}}</ref>

The [[European Research Group]] (ERG), a research support group of Eurosceptic Conservative MPs, opposed the Prime Minister's proposed Withdrawal Agreement treaty. Its members objected strongly to the Withdrawal Agreement's inclusion of the [[Irish backstop]].<ref>{{cite news |first1=Jessica |last1=Elgot |first2=Heather |last2=Stewart |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jan/28/brexiter-mps-back-away-from-anti-backstop-brexit-amendment |title=Theresa May splits Tories over anti-backstop Brexit deal |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190226234115/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jan/28/brexiter-mps-back-away-from-anti-backstop-brexit-amendment |archive-date=26 February 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=28 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Laura |last=Hughes |url=https://www.ft.com/content/3e102106-ff00-11e8-ac00-57a2a826423e |title=Eurosceptics still defiant over May's Brexit deal |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190226235625/https://www.ft.com/content/3e102106-ff00-11e8-ac00-57a2a826423e |archive-date=26 February 2019 |work=Financial Times |date=13 December 2018}}</ref> ERG members also objected to the proposed £39&nbsp;billion financial settlement with the EU and stated that the agreement would result in the UK's agreement to continuing to follow EU regulations in major policy areas; and to the continuing jurisdiction of the ECJ over interpretation of the agreement and of European law still applicable to the UK.<ref>{{cite news |first=William |last=Booth |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2018/11/24/86b536a2-ef6b-11e8-96d4-0d23f2aaad09_story.html |title=May's plan for phasing Britain out of the E.U. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190226235549/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2018/11/24/86b536a2-ef6b-11e8-96d4-0d23f2aaad09_story.html |archive-date=26 February 2019 |newspaper=Washington Post |date=25 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Jack |last=Maidment |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2018/11/18/eurosceptic-tories-publish-takedown-theresa-mays-brexit-deal/ |title=Eurosceptic Tories publish analysis of Theresa May's Brexit deal and claim UK could pay EU £39bn 'for nothing' |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190226234152/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2018/11/18/eurosceptic-tories-publish-takedown-theresa-mays-brexit-deal/ |archive-date=26 February 2019 |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=18 November 2018}}</ref>

On 15 January 2019, the House of Commons voted 432 to 202 against the deal, which was the largest majority ever against a United Kingdom government.<ref name="Brexit: Theresa May's deal is voted down in historic Commons defeat">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-46885828|title=Brexit: Theresa May's deal is voted down in historic Commons defeat|date=15 January 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=16 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430130037/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-46885828|archive-date=30 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/ng-interactive/2019/jan/15/how-did-your-mp-vote-on-mays-brexit-deal-meaningful-vote|title=How did your MP vote on May's Brexit deal?|last1=Voce|first1=Antonio|work=The Guardian|access-date=15 January 2019|last2=Clarke|first2=Seán|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|last3=Voce|first3=Antonio|last4=Clarke|first4=Seán|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190714042332/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/ng-interactive/2019/jan/15/how-did-your-mp-vote-on-mays-brexit-deal-meaningful-vote|archive-date=14 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Soon after, [[2019 motion of no confidence in the May ministry|a motion of no confidence in Her Majesty's Government was tabled by the opposition]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jan/15/theresa-may-loses-brexit-deal-vote-by-majority-of-230|title=Theresa May loses Brexit deal vote by majority of 230|last=Stewart|first=Heather|date=15 January 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=15 January 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713150628/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jan/15/theresa-may-loses-brexit-deal-vote-by-majority-of-230|archive-date=13 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> which was rejected by 325 votes to 306.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/01/16/brexit-no-confidence-vote-result-theresa-may-news-latest/|title=No confidence vote result: Theresa May wins confidence vote but is snubbed by Jeremy Corbyn over cross-party Brexit talks|last1=Rayner|first1=Gordon|date=16 January 2019|work=The Telegraph|access-date=17 January 2019|last2=Maidment|first2=Jack|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235|last3=Crisp|first3=James|last4=Yorke|first4=Harry|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416171609/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/01/16/brexit-no-confidence-vote-result-theresa-may-news-latest/|archive-date=16 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 24 February, Prime Minister May proposed that the next vote on the withdrawal agreement would be on 12 March 2019, 17 days away from the Brexit date.<ref>{{cite news|title=Another delay: Britain's May promises Brexit vote in parliament by March 12|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-may/another-delay-britains-may-promises-brexit-vote-in-parliament-by-march-12-idUSKCN1QD0J9|publisher=[[Reuters]]|date=24 February 2019|access-date=23 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190524022507/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-may/another-delay-britains-may-promises-brexit-vote-in-parliament-by-march-12-idUSKCN1QD0J9|archive-date=24 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On 12 March, the proposal was defeated by 391 votes to 242{{mdash}}a loss by 149 votes, down from 230 from when the deal had been proposed in January.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-47547887|title=Brexit: MPs reject Theresa May's deal for a second time|date=13 March 2019|work=BBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190313043330/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-47547887|archive-date=13 March 2019|url-status=live|access-date=19 March 2019}}</ref>

On 18 March 2019, the [[Speaker of the House of Commons (United Kingdom)|Speaker]] informed the House of Commons that a third meaningful vote could be held only on a [[Motion (parliamentary procedure)|motion]] that was significantly different from the previous one, citing parliamentary precedents going back to 1604.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-47614074|title=Third Brexit vote must be different – Speaker|date=18 March 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=18 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190318160131/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-47614074|archive-date=18 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

The Withdrawal Agreement was brought back to the House without the attached understandings on 29 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-47742395|title=Brexit: MPs face new vote on withdrawal deal|date=29 March 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=29 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329053108/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-47742395|archive-date=29 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The Government's motion of support for the Withdrawal Agreement was defeated by 344 votes to 286{{mdash}}a loss by 58 votes, down from 149 when the deal had been proposed on 12 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-47752017|title=Brexit: Brexit: MPs reject May's EU withdrawal agreement|date=29 March 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=29 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329145334/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-47752017|archive-date=29 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Article 50 extensions and Johnson's agreement===
On 20 March 2019, the Prime Minister wrote to European Council President Tusk requesting that Brexit be postponed until 30 June 2019.<ref>{{Cite news |date=20 March 2019 |title=Brexit: 'Tired' public needs a decision, says Theresa May |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-47647515 |url-status=live |access-date=21 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321015120/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-47647515 |archive-date=21 March 2019}}</ref> On 21 March 2019, May presented her case to a European Council summit meeting in Brussels. After May left the meeting, a discussion amongst the remaining EU leaders resulted in the rejection of 30 June date and offered instead a choice of two new alternative Brexit dates. On 22 March 2019, the extension options were agreed between the British government and the European Council.<ref name=SI2019-03-28a/> The first alternative offered was that if MPs rejected May's deal in the next week, Brexit would be due to occur by 12 April 2019, with, or without, a deal—or alternatively another extension be asked for and a commitment to participate in the [[2019 European Parliament election]]s given. The second alternative offered was that if MPs approved May's deal, Brexit would be due to occur on 22 May 2019. The later date was the day before the start of European Parliament elections.<ref name="BBC_20190322">{{Cite news |date=22 March 2019 |title=Brexit: Theresa May to urge MPs to back deal as delay agreed |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-47663031 |url-status=live |access-date=22 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190322051804/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-47663031 |archive-date=22 March 2019}}</ref> After the government deemed unwarranted the concerns over the legality of the proposed change (because it contained two possible exit dates) the previous day,<ref name="TWFY2019-03-26a">{{Cite web |date=26 March 2019 |title=Amendment to the Motion – Business of the House – Motion to Agree – in the House of Lords at 3:06 pm on 26th&nbsp;March 2019. |url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/lords/?id=2019-03-26b.1715.1 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328104029/https://www.theyworkforyou.com/lords/?id=2019-03-26b.1715.1 |archive-date=28 March 2019 |access-date=28 March 2019 |publisher=[[TheyWorkForYou]] |quote=...{{nbsp}}Lord Pannick:{{nbsp}}... A number of lawyers have expressed concern about the legality of this statutory instrument. The concern is that it sets out two alternative exit days: 12 April or 22 May.}}</ref> on 27 March 2019 both the Lords (without a vote)<ref name="Guardian2019-03-27a">{{Cite web |last1=Sparrow |first1=Andrew |author-link=Andrew Sparrow |last2=Otte |first2=Jedidajah |date=27 March 2019 |title=All eight indicative vote options on Brexit defeated by MPs – as it happened |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2019/mar/27/brexit-latest-news-live-debate-indicative-votes--to-vote-on-alternative-votes-as-speculation-mounts-may-could-announce-plans-to-quit-live-news?page=with:block-5c9bdf12e4b08334583633d3 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328080933/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2019/mar/27/brexit-latest-news-live-debate-indicative-votes--to-vote-on-alternative-votes-as-speculation-mounts-may-could-announce-plans-to-quit-live-news?page=with:block-5c9bdf12e4b08334583633d3 |archive-date=28 March 2019 |access-date=28 March 2019 |website=The Guardian |quote=The statutory instrument needs to be passed by both the Commons and the Lords. In the Lords peers passed it earlier today, without a division}}</ref> and the Commons (by 441 to 105) approved the statutory instrument changing the exit date to 22 May 2019 if a withdrawal deal is approved, or 12 April 2019 if it is not.<ref name="FT2019-03-27a">{{Cite news |last=Thomas |first=Daniel |date=27 March 2019 |title=MPs vote down rival Brexit plans as May offers to resign – as it happened |work=Financial Times |url=https://www.ft.com/content/ec9ee89c-a1a7-3c88-a8c3-3818f3781d4f |url-status=live |access-date=28 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328074207/https://www.ft.com/content/ec9ee89c-a1a7-3c88-a8c3-3818f3781d4f |archive-date=28 March 2019 |quote=MPs delay Brexit date by 441 to 105}}</ref> The amendment was then signed into law at 12:40&nbsp;p.m. the next day.<ref name=SI2019-03-28a/>

Following the failure of the British Parliament to approve the Withdrawal Agreement by 29 March, the UK was required to leave the EU on 12 April 2019. On 10 April 2019, late-night talks in Brussels resulted in a further extension, to 31 October 2019; [[Theresa May]] had again requested an extension only until 30 June. Under the terms of this new extension, if the Withdrawal Agreement were to be passed before October, Brexit would occur on the first day of the subsequent month. The UK would then be obligated to hold European Parliament elections in May or leave the EU on 1 June without a deal.<ref>{{Cite news |date=11 April 2019 |title=New Brexit deadline set for 31&nbsp;October |language=en-GB |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-47889404 |url-status=live |access-date=11 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411015652/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-47889404 |archive-date=11 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=European Council |date=10 April 2019 |title=Special meeting of the European Council (Art. 50) (10&nbsp;April 2019) – Conclusions |url=https://www.consilium.europa.eu/media/39042/10-euco-art50-conclusions-en.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411085340/https://www.consilium.europa.eu/media/39042/10-euco-art50-conclusions-en.pdf |archive-date=11 April 2019 |access-date=11 April 2019}}</ref>

In granting the Article 50 extensions, the EU adopted a stance of refusing to "reopen" (that is, renegotiate) the Withdrawal Agreement.<ref>{{Cite web |date=21 March 2019 |title=European Council Art. 50 conclusions, 21 March 2019 |url=https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2019/03/21/european-council-art-50-conclusions-21-march-2019/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191023020612/https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2019/03/21/european-council-art-50-conclusions-21-march-2019/ |archive-date=23 October 2019 |access-date=20 December 2019 |publisher=European Council}}</ref> After [[Boris Johnson]] became prime minister on 24 July 2019 and met with EU leaders, the EU changed its stance. On 17 October 2019, following "tunnel talks" between UK and EU,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Walker |first=Peter |date=11 October 2019 |title=Entering 'the tunnel': what does it mean for the Brexit talks? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/11/entering-the-tunnel-what-does-it-mean-for-brexit-talks |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017024529/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/11/entering-the-tunnel-what-does-it-mean-for-brexit-talks |archive-date=17 October 2019 |access-date=17 October 2019 |website=The Guardian}}</ref> a revised withdrawal agreement was agreed on negotiators level, and endorsed by the British government and the EU Commission.<ref>{{Cite web |date=17 October 2019 |title=European Commission Recommendation |url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/sites/beta-political/files/c2019_8000_7_en_act.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017132754/https://ec.europa.eu/commission/sites/beta-political/files/c2019_8000_7_en_act.pdf |archive-date=17 October 2019 |access-date=17 October 2019 |publisher=European Commission}}</ref> The revised deal contained a new [[Northern Ireland Protocol]], as well as technical modifications to related articles.<ref name="Europa17oct19" /> In addition, the Political Declaration was also revised.<ref>{{Cite web |date=17 October 2019 |title=Revised Political Declaration |url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/sites/beta-political/files/revised_political_declaration.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017135747/https://ec.europa.eu/commission/sites/beta-political/files/revised_political_declaration.pdf |archive-date=17 October 2019 |access-date=17 October 2019 |publisher=European Commission}}</ref> The revised deal and the political declaration was endorsed by the [[European Council]] later that day.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Kirby |first=Jen |date=17 October 2019 |title=The UK and EU have a new Brexit agreement. But it's not a done deal yet. |url=https://www.vox.com/world/2019/10/17/20918879/brexit-deal-boris-johnson-european-union-irish-backstop |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102022613/https://www.vox.com/world/2019/10/17/20918879/brexit-deal-boris-johnson-european-union-irish-backstop |archive-date=2 January 2020 |access-date=1 February 2020 |publisher=Vox}}</ref> To come into effect, it needed to be ratified by the [[European Parliament]] and the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]].<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Herszenhorn |first1=David M. |last2=Casalicchio |first2=Emilio |last3=Courea |first3=Eleni |date=17 October 2019 |title=EU and UK say they have Brexit deal |work=Politico |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/eu-and-uk-say-they-have-brexit-deal/ |url-status=live |access-date=17 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017113546/https://www.politico.eu/article/eu-and-uk-say-they-have-brexit-deal/ |archive-date=17 October 2019}}</ref>

The British Parliament passed the [[European Union (Withdrawal) (No. 2) Act 2019]], which received [[Royal Assent]] on 9 September 2019, obliging the Prime Minister to seek a third extension if no agreement has been reached at the next European Council meeting in October 2019.<ref>{{cite act|date=9 September 2019|title=European Union (Withdrawal) (No. 2) Act 2019|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2019/26|access-date=14 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190929042010/http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2019/26|archive-date=29 September 2019|url-status=live}} {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190929042010/http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2019/26 |date=29 September 2019 }}</ref> In order for such an extension to be granted if it is requested by the Prime Minister, it would be necessary for there to be unanimous agreement by all other heads of EU governments.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Kraemer |first=Daniel |date=27 September 2019 |title=Can a no-deal Brexit still happen? |language=en-GB |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49612757 |url-status=live |access-date=1 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001051353/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49612757 |archive-date=1 October 2019}}</ref> On 28 October 2019, the third extension was agreed to by the EU, with a new withdrawal deadline of 31 January 2020.<ref>{{Cite news |date=28 October 2019 |title=Brexit: European leaders agree extension to 31 January |language=en-GB |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50205603 |url-status=live |access-date=28 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191028093707/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50205603 |archive-date=28 October 2019}}</ref> 'Exit day' in British law was then amended to this new date by statutory instrument on 30 October 2019.<ref name=SI2019-10-30a/>

=== 2019 UK general election ===
{{see also|2019 United Kingdom general election}}
[[File:2019UKElectionMap.svg|right|thumb|upright=1.35|A map presenting the results of the 2019 United Kingdom general election, by party of the MP elected from each constituency]]
After Johnson was unable to induce Parliament to approve a revised version of the [[withdrawal agreement]] by the end of October, he chose to call for a [[snap election]]. Due to the fact three motions for an early general election under the [[Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011]] failed to achieve the necessary two-thirds super majority for it to pass so instead, in order to circumvent the existing law, the Government introduced an "[[Early Parliamentary General Election Act 2019|election bill]]" which only needed a simple majority of MPs to vote in favour into the House of Commons which was passed by 438–20, setting the election date for Thursday 12 December.<ref>{{cite news|date=29 October 2019|title=UK set for 12 December general election|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50229318|access-date=22 December 2019|archive-date=3 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191103131820/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50229318|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Opinion polling for the 2019 United Kingdom general election|Opinion polls]] up to polling day showed a firm lead for the Conservatives against Labour throughout the campaign.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stewart|first1=Heather|date=12 December 2019|title=Exit poll predicts 86-seat majority for Boris Johnson and Conservatives|work=[[The Guardian]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/dec/12/exit-poll-predicts-majority-for-boris-johnson-and-conservatives|access-date=19 December 2020|archive-date=13 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191213202139/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/dec/12/exit-poll-predicts-majority-for-boris-johnson-and-conservatives|url-status=live}}</ref>

In the run-up to the general election on 12 December 2019 the Conservative Party pledged to leave the EU with the withdrawal agreement negotiated in October 2019. Labour promised to renegotiate aforementioned deal and hold a referendum, letting voters choose between the renegotiated deal and remain. The Liberal Democrats vowed to revoke Article 50, while the SNP intended to hold a second referendum, however, revoking Article 50 if the alternative was a no-deal exit. The DUP supported Brexit but would seek to change parts related to Northern Ireland it was dissatisfied with. [[Plaid Cymru]] and the [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] backed a second referendum, believing the UK should stay in the EU. The [[Brexit Party]] was the only major party running for election which wanted the UK to leave the EU without a deal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Where do the parties stand on Brexit?|work=BBC News|date=5 December 2019|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-48027580|access-date=13 September 2020|archive-date=30 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191130173357/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-48027580|url-status=live}}</ref>

The election produced a decisive result for Boris Johnson with the Conservatives winning 365 seats (gaining 47 seats) and an overall majority of 80 seats with Labour suffering their worst election defeat since 1935 after losing 60 seats to leave them with 202 seats and only a single seat in [[Scotland]]. The Liberal Democrats won just 11 seats with their leader [[Jo Swinson]] losing her own seat. The Scottish National Party won 48 seats after gaining 14 seats in Scotland.

The result broke the [[Parliamentary votes on Brexit|deadlock in the UK Parliament]] and ended the possibility of a [[Proposed referendum on the Brexit withdrawal agreement|referendum being held on the withdrawal agreement]] and ensured that the [[United Kingdom]] would leave the [[European Union]] on 31 January 2020.

===Ratification and departure===
[[File:Westminster (49470617471).jpg|right|thumb|[[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] illuminated in the colours of the [[Union Jack]] on 31 January 2020]]
Subsequently, the government introduced a bill to ratify the withdrawal agreement. It passed its second reading in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] in a 358–234 vote on 20 December 2019,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/dec/20/brexit-pm-asks-britons-to-move-on-as-mps-debate-withdrawal-bill|title=Brexit: parliament passes withdrawal agreement bill by 124 majority|last=Stewart|first=Heather|date=20 December 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=20 December 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191220113442/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/dec/20/brexit-pm-asks-britons-to-move-on-as-mps-debate-withdrawal-bill|archive-date=20 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and became law on 23 January 2020 as the [[European Union (Withdrawal Agreement) Act 2020]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-politics-51221727/brexit-bill-receives-royal-assent|title=Brexit bill receives Royal Assent|date=23 January 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=2 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201235201/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-politics-51221727/brexit-bill-receives-royal-assent|archive-date=1 February 2020}}</ref>

The withdrawal agreement received the backing of the [[European Parliament Committee on Constitutional Affairs|constitutional committee]] in the [[European Parliament]] on 23 January 2020, setting expectation that the entire parliament would approve it in a later vote.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-23/brexit-deal-passes-penultimate-eu-hurdle-with-committee-approval|title=Brexit Deal Passes Penultimate EU Hurdle With Committee Approval|last=Wishart|first=Ian|date=23 January 2020|work=Bloomberg|access-date=27 January 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126193820/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-23/brexit-deal-passes-penultimate-eu-hurdle-with-committee-approval|archive-date=26 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-51244126|title=Brexit: Boris Johnson signs withdrawal agreement in Downing Street|date=24 January 2020|access-date=27 January 2020|url-status=live|work=BBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125041950/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-51244126|archive-date=25 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/22/world/europe/brexit-withdrawal-bill.html|title=U.K. Takes a Major Step Toward Brexit|last=Castle|first=Stephen|date=22 January 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=27 January 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126044640/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/22/world/europe/brexit-withdrawal-bill.html|archive-date=26 January 2020}}</ref> On the following day, [[Ursula von der Leyen]] and [[Charles Michel]] signed the withdrawal agreement in Brussels, and it was sent to London where [[Boris Johnson]] signed it.<ref name="Guardian2020jan24"/> The European Parliament gave its consent to ratification on 29 January by 621 votes to 49.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/european-parliament-ratifies-boris-johnsons-brexit-deal-ahead-of-exit-day-11921016|title=European Parliament ratifies Boris Johnson's Brexit deal ahead of exit day|last=McGuinness|first=Alan|date=29 January 2020|work=Sky News|access-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129195015/https://news.sky.com/story/european-parliament-ratifies-boris-johnsons-brexit-deal-ahead-of-exit-day-11921016|archive-date=29 January 2020}}</ref><ref name="sparrow1"/> Immediately after voting approval, members of the European Parliament joined hands and sang ''[[Auld Lang Syne]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/video-european-parliament-sings-auld-lang-syne-after-approving-brexit-2020-1|title=The European Parliament joined hands and sang Auld Lang Syne in an emotional Brexit farewell to the UK|last=Payne|first=Adam|date=30 January 2020|agency=Reuters|publisher=Business Insider|access-date=1 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131154336/https://www.businessinsider.com/video-european-parliament-sings-auld-lang-syne-after-approving-brexit-2020-1|archive-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Council of the European Union]] concluded EU ratification the following day.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/30/world/europe/eu-brexit-decision.html|last=Stevis-Gridneff|first=Matina|title=Press send for Brexit: E.U. seals U.K. withdrawal by email|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=30 January 2020|access-date=8 July 2020|archive-date=31 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131154556/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/30/world/europe/eu-brexit-decision.html|url-status=dead}}</ref> At 11 p.m. [[GMT]], 31 January 2020, the United Kingdom's membership of the European Union ended, 47 years after it had joined.<ref name="autogenerated1" /> As confirmed by the [[Court of Justice of the European Union|Court of Justice]] in ''EP v Préfet du Gers'',<ref>{{Citation |title=EP v Préfet du Gers and Institut national de la statistique et des études économiques (INSEE) |date=9 June 2022 |url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/en/TXT/?uri=CELEX:62020CJ0673 |issue=Case C-673/20 |access-date=24 July 2023 |language=en |archive-date=21 July 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230721131205/https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/en/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A62020CJ0673 |url-status=live }}</ref> all British nationals ceased to be Union citizens.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Lashyn |first=Serhii |date=2022 |title=Sacrificing EU citizenship on the altar of Brexit |journal=Maastricht Journal of European and Comparative Law |language=en |volume=29 |issue=6 |pages=736–744 |doi=10.1177/1023263X221146465 |issn=1023-263X|doi-access=free }}</ref>

===Transition period and final trade agreement===
[[File:Trim.124028DB-3986-4A22-BE88-3024C92E0C3A.webm|thumb|left|Conservative party advertisement from early 2020 featuring Boris Johnson answering frequently searched for online Brexit-related questions]]
Following the British exit on 31 January 2020 the UK entered a Transition Period for the rest of 2020. Trade, travel and freedom of movement remain largely unchanged during this period.<ref name="transition">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-50838994 |newspaper=BBC News |title=Brexit: What is the transition period? |first=Tom |last=Edgington |date=20 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201075405/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-50838994 |archive-date=1 February 2020 }}</ref>

The Withdrawal Agreement still applies after this date.<ref name="eu-sues-wa"/> This agreement [[Brexit withdrawal agreement#Northern Ireland|provides]] free access of goods between Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland, provided checks are made to goods entering Northern Ireland from the rest of the UK. The British Government attempted to back out of this commitment<ref name="specific">{{cite news |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/uk/brexit-britain-says-it-may-break-international-law-in-limited-way-1.4349653 |newspaper=The Irish Times |title=Brexit: Britain says it may break international law in 'limited way' |date=8 September 2020 |access-date=1 November 2020 |archive-date=18 September 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200918143030/https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/uk/brexit-britain-says-it-may-break-international-law-in-limited-way-1.4349653 |url-status=live }}</ref> by passing the [[Internal Market Bill]]: domestic legislation in the British Parliament. In September, Northern Ireland secretary [[Brandon Lewis]] said:

{{blockquote|I would say to my hon. Friend that yes, this does break international law in a very specific and limited way.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/debates/?id=2020-09-08c.497.0&s=%22very+specific+and+limited+way%22#g509.0 |title=Northern Ireland Protocol: UK Legal Obligations |publisher=TheyWorkForYou |date=8 September 2020 |access-date=1 November 2020 }}</ref>}}

leading to the resignation of [[Jonathan Jones (civil servant)|Sir Jonathan Jones]], permanent secretary to the Government Legal Department<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-54072347 |work=BBC News |title=Senior government lawyer quits over Brexit plans |date=8 September 2020 |access-date=1 November 2020 |archive-date=6 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201106183325/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-54072347 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[Lord Keen]], the law officer for Scotland.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-54179745 |title=Lord Keen: Senior law officer quits over Brexit bill row |date=16 September 2020 |work=BBC News |access-date=1 November 2020 |archive-date=1 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201101002000/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-54179745 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[European Commission]] started legal action.<ref name="eu-sues-wa">{{cite news |last1=Boffey |first1=Daniel |last2=O'Carroll |first2=Lisa |title=Brexit: EU launches legal action against UK for breaching withdrawal agreement |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/oct/01/brexit-eu-launches-legal-action-against-uk-for-breaching-withdrawal-agreement |access-date=1 November 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=1 October 2020 |archive-date=17 December 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201217125215/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/oct/01/brexit-eu-launches-legal-action-against-uk-for-breaching-withdrawal-agreement |url-status=live }}</ref>

During the transition period, David Frost and Michel Barnier continued to [[Trade negotiation between the UK and the EU|negotiate a permanent trade agreement]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Boffey |first1=Daniel |last2=Borger |first2=Julian |title=Brexit talks to resume after Michel Barnier speech breaks impasse |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/oct/21/uk-welcomes-barnier-significant-remarks-on-unlocking-brexit-talks |access-date=2 May 2021 |work=The Guardian |date=21 October 2020 |archive-date=7 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210607093242/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/oct/21/uk-welcomes-barnier-significant-remarks-on-unlocking-brexit-talks |url-status=live }}</ref> On 24 December 2020 both parties announced that a deal had been reached.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Boffey |first1=Daniel |last2=O'Carroll |first2=Lisa |title=UK and EU agree Brexit trade deal |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/dec/24/uk-eu-agree-brexit-trade-deal-agreement |access-date=25 December 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=24 December 2020 |archive-date=29 December 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201229024159/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/dec/24/uk-eu-agree-brexit-trade-deal-agreement |url-status=live }}</ref> The deal was passed by both houses of the British parliament on 30 December and given Royal Assent in the early hours of the next day. In the House of Commons, the governing Conservatives and main opposition Labour voted in favour of the agreement whilst all other opposition parties voted against it.<ref>{{cite news|date=30 December 2020|title=Brexit: MPs overwhelmingly back post-Brexit deal with EU|language=en-GB|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-55478513|access-date=30 December 2020|archive-date=30 December 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201230163525/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-55478513|url-status=live}}</ref> The transition period concluded under its terms the following evening.<ref>{{cite news|date=31 December 2020|title=Brexit: New era for UK as it completes separation from European Union|language=en-GB|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-55502781|access-date=1 January 2021|archive-date=14 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210114212309/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-55502781|url-status=live}}</ref> After the UK said it would unilaterally extend a [[Northern Ireland Protocol#Grace period|grace period]] limiting checks on trade between Northern Ireland and Great Britain, the [[European Parliament]] postponed setting a date to ratify the agreement.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2021/mar/04/uks-plan-to-extend-brexit-grace-period-infuriates-irish-and-eu-officials |title=EU postpones setting date for ratifying Brexit trade deal |work=The Guardian |date=4 March 2021 |access-date=15 March 2021 |archive-date=15 April 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210415170051/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2021/mar/04/uks-plan-to-extend-brexit-grace-period-infuriates-irish-and-eu-officials |url-status=live }}</ref> The vote was later scheduled for 27 April when it passed with an overwhelming majority of votes.<ref>{{cite web|last=Blenkinsop|first=Philip|date=22 April 2021|title=EU parliament agrees to April 27 vote on EU-UK trade deal|url=https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/european-parliament-agrees-april-vote-eu-uk-trade-deal-2021-04-22/|access-date=28 April 2021|publisher=Reuters|archive-date=28 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210428100216/https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/european-parliament-agrees-april-vote-eu-uk-trade-deal-2021-04-22/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=28 April 2021|title=Brexit: European Parliament backs UK trade deal|language=en-GB|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-56899831|access-date=28 April 2021|archive-date=27 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210427230040/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-56899831|url-status=live}}</ref>

There was a customs transitional arrangement in place until 1 July 2021. During this time period, traders importing standard goods from the EU to the UK could defer submitting their customs declarations and paying import duties to HMRC for up to six months. This arrangement simplified and avoided most import controls during the early months of the new situation and was designed to facilitate inward trade during the COVID-19 health crisis and to avoid major disruptions in domestic supply chains in the short term.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rankin |first1=Jennifer |last2=O'Carroll |first2=Lisa |title=Brexit: full controls on goods entering UK will not apply until July 2021 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jun/12/brexit-full-border-controls-on-goods-entering-uk-will-not-apply-until-july-2021 |work=The Guardian |date=12 June 2020 |access-date=1 May 2021 |archive-date=1 May 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210501073245/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jun/12/brexit-full-border-controls-on-goods-entering-uk-will-not-apply-until-july-2021 |url-status=live }}</ref> Following reports that the border infrastructure was not ready, the UK government further postponed import checks from the EU to the UK until the end of the year in order to avoid supply issues during the ongoing Covid crisis.<ref>{{cite news |last=Partridge |first=Joanna |title=UK forced to delay checks on imports from EU by six months |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2021/mar/11/uk-forced-to-delay-import-checks-on-eu-goods-by-six-months-2022-border-post-not-ready |work=The Guardian |date=11 March 2021 |access-date=22 June 2021 |archive-date=24 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210624205539/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2021/mar/11/uk-forced-to-delay-import-checks-on-eu-goods-by-six-months-2022-border-post-not-ready |url-status=live }}</ref> This was again followed by another delay of import controls, in a situation of truck driver shortages; the controls are scheduled to be phased in during 2022.<ref>{{cite news |last=Holton |first=Kate |title=Britain delays post-Brexit import trade controls again |url=https://www.reuters.com/world/uk/britain-delays-implementation-post-brexit-trade-controls-2021-09-14/ |access-date=25 September 2021 |publisher=Reuters |date=14 September 2021 |archive-date=25 September 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210925064909/https://www.reuters.com/world/uk/britain-delays-implementation-post-brexit-trade-controls-2021-09-14/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

== United Kingdom legislation after Article 50 notification==

===European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018===
{{main|European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018}}
In October 2016, Theresa May promised a "Great Repeal Bill", which would repeal the [[European Communities Act 1972 (UK)|European Communities Act 1972]] and restate in British law all enactments previously in force under EU law. Subsequently renamed the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill, it was introduced into the House of Commons on 13 July 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://services.parliament.uk/bills/2017-19/europeanunionwithdrawal.html |title=European Union (Withdrawal) Bill 2017–19 – UK Parliament |publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom |access-date=23 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725141501/https://services.parliament.uk/bills/2017-19/europeanunionwithdrawal.html |archive-date=25 July 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>

On 12 September 2017, the Bill passed its first vote and second reading by a margin of 326 votes to 290 votes in the House of Commons.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-41235522 |title=EU repeal bill wins first Commons vote |date=12 September 2017 |access-date=1 November 2017 |work=BBC News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727155411/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-41235522 |archive-date=27 July 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The Bill was further amended on a series of votes in both Houses. After the Act became law on 26 June 2018, the European Council decided on 29 June to renew its call on member states and European Union institutions to step up their work on preparedness at all levels and for all outcomes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/media/35966/29-euco-art50-conclusions-en.pdf |title=Conclusions adopted by the European Council (Art. 50), 29&nbsp;June 2018 |website=europa.eu |access-date=2 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190214172737/https://www.consilium.europa.eu/media/35966/29-euco-art50-conclusions-en.pdf |archive-date=14 February 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>

The Withdrawal Act fixed the period ending 21 January 2019 for the government to decide on how to proceed if the negotiations had not reached agreement in principle on both the withdrawal arrangements and the framework for the future relationship between the UK and EU; while, alternatively, making future ratification of the withdrawal agreement as a treaty between the UK and EU depend upon the prior enactment of another act of Parliament for approving the final terms of withdrawal when the [[Brexit negotiations]] were completed. In any event, the Act did not alter the two-year period for negotiating allowed by Article 50 that ended at the latest on 29 March 2019 if the UK had not by then ratified a withdrawal agreement or agreed a prolongation of the negotiating period.<ref name=ExitDay01a/>

The Withdrawal Act which became law in June 2018 allowed for various outcomes including no negotiated settlement. It authorises the government to bring into force, by [[Statutory instrument (UK)|order]] made under section 25, the provisions that fixed "exit day" and the repeal of the European Communities Act 1972 but exit day must be the same day and time as when the EU Treaties ceased to apply to the UK.<ref>{{cite web |last=Cowie |first=Graeme |title=What is "exit day"? Dispelling misconceptions about the extension of Article 50 |url=https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/what-is-exit-day-dispelling-misconceptions-about-the-extension-of-article-50/ |url-status=live |website=commonslibrary.parliament.uk |publisher=House of Commons Library |date=19 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210516131529/https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/what-is-exit-day-dispelling-misconceptions-about-the-extension-of-article-50/ |archive-date=16 May 2021}}</ref>

===Exit day===
Exit day was the end of 31 January 2020 [[Central European Time|CET]] (11.00 p.m. [[GMT]]).<ref name=SI2019-10-30a>{{cite web|title=The European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018 (Exit Day) (Amendment) (No. 3) Regulations 2019 |id=SI 2019 No. 1423 |date=30 October 2019 |url=https://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2019/1423/made |website=legislation.gov.uk |publisher=The National Archives |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115183425/http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2019/1423/made |archive-date=15 November 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The [[European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018]] (as amended by a British [[Statutory Instrument]] on 11 April 2019), in section 20 (1), defined 'exit day' as 11:00&nbsp;p.m. on 31 October 2019.<ref name=SI2019-03-28a>{{cite web|title=Statutory Instruments – 2019 No. 859 – Exiting The European Union – The European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018 (Exit Day) (Amendment) (No. 2) Regulations 2019 |url=https://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2019/859/pdfs/uksi_20190859_en.pdf|date=11 April 2019 |access-date=13 April 2019 |publisher=[[The Stationery Office Limited]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417225120/http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2019/859/pdfs/uksi_20190859_en.pdf |archive-date=17 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Originally, 'exit day' was defined as 11:00&nbsp;p.m. on 29 March 2019 GMT ([[UTC+0]]).<ref name=ExitDay01a>{{cite web |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2018/16/contents/enacted/data.htm |website=legislation.gov.uk |title=European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018<!-- Ch. 16 --> |access-date=13 February 2019 |date=2018 |quote="exit day" means 29 March 2019 at 11.00 p.m.(and see subsections (2) to (5)); |at=sec.&nbsp;20(1) |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190206234328/http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2018/16/contents/enacted/data.htm|archive-date=6 February 2019|url-status=live}} Subsections (2) to (5) provide the option of amending the date by a Ministerial Regulation "if the day or time on or at which the Treaties are to cease to apply to the United Kingdom in accordance with Article 50(3) of the Treaty on European Union is different from that specified in the definition of 'exit day' in subsection (1)." (Article 50(3) of the [[Treaty on European Union]] states: "The Treaties shall cease to apply to the State in question from the date of entry into force of the withdrawal agreement or, failing that, two years after the notification referred to in paragraph 2, unless the European Council, in agreement with the Member State concerned, unanimously decides to extend this period".)</ref><ref name="reuters1">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-timeline/key-dates-in-brexit-process-idUSKBN1FM2H9|title=Key dates in Brexit process|date=2 February 2018|publisher=Reuters|access-date=13 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180924163923/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-timeline/key-dates-in-brexit-process-idUSKBN1FM2H9|archive-date=24 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Walker |first=Nigel |title=Brexit timeline: events leading to the UK's exit from the European Union |url=https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/research-briefings/cbp-7960/ |url-status=live |type=Research briefing |website=commonslibrary.parliament.uk |publisher=House of Commons Library |date=6 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210813211646/https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/research-briefings/cbp-7960/ |archive-date=13 August 2021 }}</ref>

===Additional government bills===
A report published in March 2017 by the [[Institute for Government]] commented that, in addition to the European Union (Withdrawal) bill, primary and secondary legislation would be needed to cover the gaps in policy areas such as customs, immigration and agriculture.<ref>{{cite web |last1=White |first1=Hannah |last2=Rutter |first2=Jill |title=Legislating Brexit: The Great Repeal Bill and the wider legislative challenge |website=instituteforgovernment.org.uk |date=March 2017 |page=9 |url=https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/sites/default/files/publications/IFGJ5347-Legislating-Brexit-IFG-Analysis-032017-WEB.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170321154433/https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/sites/default/files/publications/IFGJ5347-Legislating-Brexit-IFG-Analysis-032017-WEB.pdf |archive-date=21 March 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> The report also commented that the role of the devolved legislatures was unclear, and could cause problems, and that as many as 15 new additional Brexit Bills might be required, which would involve strict prioritisation and limiting Parliamentary time for in-depth examination of new legislation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39322297|title=Brexit could place 'huge burden' on Parliament|work=BBC News|date=20 March 2017|access-date=29 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727015516/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39322297|archive-date=27 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

