====Nuclear Safeguards Act 2018====
The [[Nuclear Safeguards Act 2018]], relating to withdrawal from Euratom, was presented to Parliament in October 2017. The act makes provision about nuclear safeguards, and for connected purposes. The Secretary of State may by regulations ("nuclear safeguards regulations") make provision for the purpose of&nbsp;– (a) ensuring that qualifying nuclear material, facilities or equipment are available only for use for civil activities (whether in the UK or elsewhere), or (b) giving effect to provisions of a relevant international agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2018/15/pdfs/ukpga_20180015_en.pdf|title=Nuclear Safeguards Act 2018|website=www.legislation.gov.uk|access-date=3 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214033335/https://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2018/15/pdfs/ukpga_20180015_en.pdf|archive-date=14 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

==== European Union (Withdrawal Agreement) Act 2020 ====
{{main|European Union (Withdrawal Agreement) Act 2020}}
The [[European Union (Withdrawal Agreement) Act 2020]] makes legal provision for ratifying the [[Brexit Withdrawal Agreement]] and incorporating it into the domestic law of the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web |title=New Bill to implement Withdrawal Agreement |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-bill-to-implement-withdrawal-agreement |publisher=[[Government of the United Kingdom]] |date=13 November 2017 |access-date=18 February 2022 |archive-date=18 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220218125425/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-bill-to-implement-withdrawal-agreement |url-status=live }}</ref> The bill was first introduced<ref>{{cite web|url=https://services.parliament.uk/Bills/2019-19/europeanunionwithdrawalagreement.html|title=European Union (Withdrawal Agreement) Bill 2019 — UK Parliament|website=services.parliament.uk|access-date=18 February 2022|archive-date=11 November 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201111175926/https://services.parliament.uk/Bills/2019-19/europeanunionwithdrawalagreement.html|url-status=live}}</ref> by the government on 21 October 2019. This bill was not further debated and lapsed on 6 November when [[Dissolution of parliament|parliament was dissolved]] in preparation for the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]]. The bill was reintroduced immediately following the general election and was the first bill to be put before the [[House of Commons]] in the first session of the 58th Parliament,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://services.parliament.uk/Bills/2019-20/europeanunionwithdrawalagreement.html|title=European Union (Withdrawal Agreement) Bill 2019–20 — UK Parliament|website=services.parliament.uk|access-date=18 February 2022|archive-date=27 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127052521/https://services.parliament.uk/Bills/2019-20/europeanunionwithdrawalagreement.html|url-status=live}}</ref> with changes from the previous bill, by the re-elected government and was [[Reading (legislature)|read a first time]] on 19 December, immediately after the first reading of the [[Outlawries Bill]] and before the debate on the [[State Opening of Parliament|Queen's Speech]] began. The second reading took place on 20 December, and the third on 9 January 2020. This act was given [[Royal Assent]] on 23 January 2020, nine days before the UK left the [[European Union]].

== Public opinion since the Brexit referendum ==
=== Prior to 2020 ===
{{further|Opinion polling on the United Kingdom's membership of the European Union (2016–2020)}}
Opinion polling overall showed an initial fall in support for Brexit from the referendum to late 2016, when responses were split evenly between support and opposition. Support rose again to a plurality, which held until the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]]. Since then, opinion polls tended to show a plurality of support for remaining in the EU or for the view that Brexit was a mistake, with the estimated margin increasing until a small decrease in 2019 (to 53% Remain: 47% Leave, {{as of|2019|10|lc=1}}).<ref name=OctoberPollOfPolls>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/brexit-news-latest-britain-against-leaving-eu-as-poll-of-polls-says-most-now-want-to-stay-a4257476.html|title=Brexit news latest: Poll of polls says Britain is now against leaving EU as most want to stay|last=Cecil|first=Nicholas|date=10 October 2019|website=Evening Standard|publisher=London Evening Standard|access-date=19 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016201243/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/brexit-news-latest-britain-against-leaving-eu-as-poll-of-polls-says-most-now-want-to-stay-a4257476.html|archive-date=16 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> This seems to be largely due to a preference for remaining in the EU among those who did not vote in 2016's referendum (an estimated 2.5 million of whom, {{As of|2019|October|lc=1}}, were [[Voting age#United Kingdom|too young to vote]] at the time).<ref name=IndependentDemographics>{{cite news|last=Kellner|first=Peter|date=10 October 2019|title=Everyone says they know what the public think about Brexit – here's the polling data that tells you who's right|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/brexit-myths-busting-polling-second-referendum-leave-remain-a9149491.html|work=The Independent|access-date=16 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016201237/https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/brexit-myths-busting-polling-second-referendum-leave-remain-a9149491.html|archive-date=16 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://whatukthinks.org/eu/has-there-been-a-shift-in-support-for-brexit/|title=Has There Been a Shift in Support for Brexit?|last=Curtice|first=John|date=8 February 2019|website=What UK Thinks|access-date=16 May 2019|quote=Until the 2017 general election typically more people said that the decision to leave the EU was right than stated it was wrong. Since then the oppose has been the case{{nbsp}}... The reason why the balance of opinion had shifted in favour of Remain, even though very few Leave voters had changed their minds, was because those who had not voted before (in some cases because they had been too young to do so) were now decisively in favour of Remain.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190516224825/https://whatukthinks.org/eu/has-there-been-a-shift-in-support-for-brexit/|archive-date=16 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Other reasons suggested include slightly more Leave voters than Remain voters (14% and 12% of each, respectively, {{as of|2019|10|lc=1}})<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-50043549 |title=Have UK voters changed their minds on Brexit? |last=Curtice |first=John |date=17 October 2019 |work=BBC News |access-date=23 October 2019 |quote=On average, during the last month, polls that ask people how they would vote in another referendum suggest that 88% of those who backed Remain would do so again. Among those who voted Leave, 86% have not changed their minds. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191023163831/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-50043549 |archive-date=23 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> changing how they would vote (particularly in [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] areas) and the deaths of older voters,<ref name=OctoberPollOfPolls /> most of whom voted to leave the EU. One estimate of demographic changes (ignoring other effects) implies that had an EU referendum taken place {{As of|alt=in October 2019|2019|10|post=,}} there would have been between 800,000 and 900,000 fewer Leave voters and between 600,000 and 700,000 more Remain voters, resulting in a Remain majority.<ref name=IndependentDemographics />

In March 2019, a [[Revoke Article 50 and remain in the EU petition|petition]] submitted to the British Parliament petitions website, calling on the government to revoke Article 50 and stay in the EU, reached a record-level of more than 6.1&nbsp;million signatures.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/mar/31/article-50-petition-to-cancel-brexit-passes-6m-signatures|title=Article 50 petition to cancel Brexit passes 6m signatures|work=The Guardian|access-date=5 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403074151/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/mar/31/article-50-petition-to-cancel-brexit-passes-6m-signatures|archive-date=3 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-47772682|title=Article 50: MPs debate six-million-signature petition|work=BBC News|access-date=5 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410101020/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-47772682|archive-date=10 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>
