=== 2020–present ===
{{further|Opinion polling on the United Kingdom rejoining the European Union (2020–present)}}
[[YouGov]] polling has shown a gradual but progressive decline in the public perception of the benefits of Brexit, with the overall margin of sentiment about the rightness of the Brexit decision declining from slightly positive in 2016 to −11% in 2022.<ref>{{cite web |date=July 2022 |title=EU Tracker Questions (GB): In hindsight, do you think Britain was right or wrong to vote to leave the European Union? |url=https://docs.cdn.yougov.com/fn8wcm524j/YG%20Trackers%20-%20EU%20Tracker%20Questions_W.pdf |access-date=5 June 2022 |website=YouGov |archive-date=2 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220602111434/https://docs.cdn.yougov.com/fn8wcm524j/YG%20Trackers%20-%20EU%20Tracker%20Questions_W.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref> A May 2022 poll showed that a majority of respondents who expressed an opinion thought that Brexit had gone either "badly" or "very badly".<ref>{{cite web |title=Daily Question {{!}} 10 May 2022 {{!}} YouGov |url=https://yougov.co.uk/topics/politics/survey-results/daily/2022/05/10/6f966/2 |access-date=5 June 2022 |website=yougov.co.uk |language=en-GB |archive-date=3 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220603143608/https://yougov.co.uk/topics/politics/survey-results/daily/2022/05/10/6f966/2 |url-status=live }}</ref> A new study showed that since Brexit, citizens in other European nations were more against leaving the EU than they had been since 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |date=12 January 2023 |title=Support for leaving EU has fallen significantly across bloc since Brexit |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/jan/12/support-for-leaving-eu-has-fallen-significantly-across-bloc-since-brexit |access-date=12 January 2023 |website=The Guardian |language=en |archive-date=12 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230112092431/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/jan/12/support-for-leaving-eu-has-fallen-significantly-across-bloc-since-brexit |url-status=live }}</ref> A January 2023 poll in the United Kingdom also reflected these numbers, with 54% of poll respondents who believed that the country was wrong to leave the European Union, while 35% of respondents believed it was the right decision.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Brexit opinion poll 2023 |url=https://www.statista.com/statistics/987347/brexit-opinion-poll/ |access-date=12 January 2023 |website=Statista |language=en |archive-date=12 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230112132202/https://www.statista.com/statistics/987347/brexit-opinion-poll/ |url-status=live }}</ref> An average of six polls conducted in June and July 2023 shows 58% of voters in favor of rejoining the EU with 42% of voters against rejoining the EU.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Post-Brexit Poll of Polls |url=https://www.whatukthinks.org/eu/opinion-polls/poll-of-polls-uk-eu/ |access-date=21 July 2023 |website=What UK Thinks: EU |language=en-US |archive-date=21 July 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230721171623/https://www.whatukthinks.org/eu/opinion-polls/poll-of-polls-uk-eu/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Since 2020, pollsters have asked respondents how they would vote in a potential second referendum to rejoin the EU.

[[File:Opinion polling on the whether the United Kingdom should rejoin the European Union.svg|center|frame|Opinion polling on whether the United Kingdom should rejoin the European Union (since January 2020)]]

==No-deal planning==
{{see also|No-deal Brexit|Operation Yellowhammer}}
On 19 December 2018, the EU Commission revealed its "no-deal" Contingency Action Plan in specific sectors, in respect of the UK leaving the EU "in 100 days' time."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-18-6851_en.htm|title=European Commission – PRESS RELEASES – Press release – Brexit: European Commission implements "no-deal" Contingency Action Plan in specific sectors|website=europa.eu|access-date=5 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905165240/https://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-18-6851_en.htm|archive-date=5 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

In the wake of the United Kingdom's vote to leave the European Union, the [[Department for International Trade]] (DIT) for reaching and extending trade agreements between the UK and non-EU states was created by Prime Minister May, shortly after she took office on 13 July 2016.<ref name="csw new article">{{cite web|url=https://www.civilserviceworld.com/articles/news/theresa-may-signals-whitehall-rejig-two-new-cabinet-posts|title=Theresa May signals Whitehall rejig with two new Cabinet posts|website=civilserviceworld.com|publisher=CSW|access-date=14 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160714151146/http://www.civilserviceworld.com/articles/news/theresa-may-signals-whitehall-rejig-two-new-cabinet-posts|archive-date=14 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> By 2017, it employed about 200 trade negotiators<ref name="economist2017">Trading places / Negotiating post-Brexit deals. Economist, 4–10 February 2017, p. 25</ref> and was overseen by then [[Secretary of State for International Trade]] [[Liam Fox]]. In March 2019, the British government announced that it would cut many import tariffs to zero, in the event of a no-deal Brexit.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/temporary-tariff-regime-for-no-deal-brexit-published|title=Temporary tariff regime for no deal Brexit published|website=GOV.UK|date=13 March 2019 |access-date=14 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329183755/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/temporary-tariff-regime-for-no-deal-brexit-published|archive-date=29 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Confederation of British Industry]] said the move would be a "sledgehammer for our economy",<ref name="Guardian2019mar13">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/mar/13/brexit-tariffs-on-87-of-uk-imports-cut-to-zero-in-temporary-no-deal-plan|title=UK will cut most tariffs to zero in event of no-deal Brexit|last1=O'Carroll|first1=Lisa|last2=Boffey|first2=Daniel|date=13 March 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=14 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190314110111/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/mar/13/brexit-tariffs-on-87-of-uk-imports-cut-to-zero-in-temporary-no-deal-plan|archive-date=14 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/uk-news/car-prices-rise-1500-no-15965400|title=Car prices to rise by £1,500 as no-deal tariffs are revealed|last1=Glaze|first1=Ben|last2=Bloom|first2=Dan|date=13 March 2019|website=walesonline|last3=Owen|first3=Cathy|access-date=14 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329172608/https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/uk-news/car-prices-rise-1500-no-15965400|archive-date=29 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.aol.co.uk/news/2019/03/13/no-deal-tariff-regime-would-be-a-sledgehammera-to-uk-economy/|title=No-deal tariff regime would be 'sledgehammer' to UK economy, CBI warns|website=Aol.co.uk|access-date=14 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329172648/https://www.aol.co.uk/news/2019/03/13/no-deal-tariff-regime-would-be-a-sledgehammera-to-uk-economy/|archive-date=29 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and the [[National Farmers' Union of England and Wales|National Farmer's Union]] was also highly critical.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/brexit-explained/brexit-no-deal-farmers-eu-tariffs-food-costs-imports-theresa-may-a8821096.html|title=This is why farmers are suddenly very worried about a no-deal Brexit|date=13 March 2019|website=The Independent|access-date=14 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329185311/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/brexit-explained/brexit-no-deal-farmers-eu-tariffs-food-costs-imports-theresa-may-a8821096.html|archive-date=29 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Additionally, the plan appeared to breach standard WTO rules.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-47551121|title=No-deal plans a bid 'to break EU unity'|date=13 March 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=14 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331063145/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-47551121|archive-date=31 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.euronews.com/2019/03/13/uk-s-zero-tariff-plan-for-no-deal-brexit-would-not-spare-some-eu-imports|title=UK zero-tariff plan for no-deal Brexit would not spare some EU imports|last=Sandford|first=Alisdair|date=13 March 2019|website=Euronews.com|format=PDF|access-date=14 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329172729/https://www.euronews.com/2019/03/13/uk-s-zero-tariff-plan-for-no-deal-brexit-would-not-spare-some-eu-imports|archive-date=29 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-eu-tariffs-idUKKBN1QU1J9|title=EU to apply normal tariffs on trade with UK in case of no-deal Brexit|date=13 March 2019|publisher=Reuters|access-date=14 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329183742/https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-eu-tariffs-idUKKBN1QU1J9|archive-date=29 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 2 June 2020, Chancellor of Germany [[Angela Merkel]] stated that the [[European Union]] must prepare for the possible failure of Brexit trade talks with the [[UK]]. She added that negotiations were being accelerated to try and reach a deal that could be ratified by the end of the year. Her warning came as the deadline for extending talks passed, with negotiations expected to end on 31 December with or without a deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-no-deal-eu-merkel-germany-trade-talks-boris-johnson-a9595511.html|title=Brexit: EU must prepare for no-deal, Merkel warns|access-date=2 June 2020|website=Independent|archive-date=1 July 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200701175318/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-no-deal-eu-merkel-germany-trade-talks-boris-johnson-a9595511.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

==Litigation==
There has been litigation to explore the constitutional footings on which Brexit stands after ''[[R (Miller) v Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union]]'' (simply known as the "Miller case") and the 2017 Notification Act:
* In ''R. (Webster) v Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union'', a [[divisional court (England and Wales)|divisional court]] of [[Peter Gross (judge)|Gross LJ]] and [[Nicholas Green (judge)|Green MR]] determined that the substantive decision to leave the EU that was notified on 29 March 2017 was in fact the executive decision of the Prime Minister using a statutory power of decision found to have been delegated to her by the Notification Act: this is confirmed by the [[House of Commons Library]] commentary on the case.<ref name="Miller">{{cite web|last1=de Mars |first1=Sylvia |last2=Miller |first2=Vaughne |url=https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/research-briefings/cbp-8415/ |title=Brexit questions in national and EU courts |publisher=House of Commons Library |website=commonslibrary.parliament.uk |date=1 November 2019 |type=Research briefing |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210224151736/https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/research-briefings/cbp-8415/ |archive-date=24 February 2021 |url-status=live}}</ref> The case was appealed to the [[Court of Appeal (England and Wales)|Court of Appeal]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.crowdjustice.com/case/a50-chall-her-e50/|title=Article 50 Challenge|work=CrowdJustice|access-date=20 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190522112547/https://www.crowdjustice.com/case/a50-chall-her-e50/|archive-date=22 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and paragraph 15 of the judgement, along with the citable nature of the decision were upheld. While the case was criticised academically by Robert Craig, who lectures in jurisprudence at the London School of Economics,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ukconstitutionallaw.org/2018/06/26/robert-craig-new-article-50-case-resoundingly-rejected-by-the-divisional-court/|title=Robert Craig: New Article 50 Case Resoundingly Rejected by the Divisional Court|date=26 June 2018|work=UK Constitutional Law Association|access-date=20 November 2018|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708132234/https://ukconstitutionallaw.org/2018/06/26/robert-craig-new-article-50-case-resoundingly-rejected-by-the-divisional-court/|archive-date=8 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> aspects of the case's analysis were supported by the [[UK Supreme Court|Supreme Court]] in [[Miller 2]] at paragraph 57, which confirmed:

{{blockquote|... that Parliament, and in particular the House of Commons as the democratically elected representatives of the people, has a right to have a voice in how that change comes about is indisputable.<ref>{{cite BAILII|litigants=R (on the application of Miller) v The Prime Minister''; ''Cherry and Others v Advocate General for Scotland|court=UKSC|year=2019|num=41|date=24 September 2019}}</ref>|source=Supreme Court of the United Kingdom (UKSC/2019/41)}}

* This confirmation that the decision was an executive act was part of the basis of [[R (Wilson) v Prime Minister|''R.'' (''Wilson) v. Prime Minister'']]<ref>{{Cite web|title=Grounds for Judicial Review in ''Susan Wilson & others -and- The Prime Minister'' |date=13 August 2018 |url=https://www.croftsolicitors.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/239484-Grounds-for-Judicial-Review-and-Statement-of-Facts.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825212619/http://www.croftsolicitors.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/239484-Grounds-for-Judicial-Review-and-Statement-of-Facts.pdf |archive-date=25 August 2018 |url-status=live |id=CO/3214/2018 |website=croftsolicitors.com}}</ref> which allied this point with the concerns about the irregularities in the referendum. The High Court hearing was on 7 December 2018 before [[Duncan Ouseley|Ouseley MJ]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ukineuchallenge.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Bremain-mailer-021118-UKEU-edit-website.pdf|title=UKEU Challenge Update|website=UKEU Challenge|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401210410/https://www.ukineuchallenge.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Bremain-mailer-021118-UKEU-edit-website.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2019|url-status=live|access-date=20 November 2018}}</ref> and when judgement was given it was held that: courts' job was not to rule on irregularities in the 'leave' campaign as these were not questions of law; it was also said that the case was brought both too early and too late.<ref name="Miller"/> Judgement in the Court of Appeal (before [[Gary Hickinbottom|Hickinbottom LJ]] and [[Charles Haddon-Cave|Haddon-Cave LJ]]) before also went against the applicant.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.judiciary.uk/publications/wilson-others-v-the-prime-minister-respondent-1-and-the-electoral-commission-respondent-2/|title=Wilson & others –v- The Prime Minister (Respondent 1) and The Electoral Commission (Respondent 2)|website=www.judiciary.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=4 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330073014/https://www.judiciary.uk/publications/wilson-others-v-the-prime-minister-respondent-1-and-the-electoral-commission-respondent-2/|archive-date=30 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>
* Regarding the reversibility of a notification under Article 50, ''Wightman and others v Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union'' was referred to the [[Court of Justice of the European Union]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/sep/21/triggering-article-50-reversed-european-court-justice-brexit-bad-dream|title=Today's ruling shows the triggering of article 50 can be reversed|last=Maugham|first=Jolyon|date=21 September 2018|website=The Guardian|access-date=20 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401210405/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/sep/21/triggering-article-50-reversed-european-court-justice-brexit-bad-dream|archive-date=1 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> the UK government sought to block this referral, taking the matter on appeal to the Supreme Court, but was unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.supremecourt.uk/docs/reasons-for-the-determination-in-the-matter-of-secretary-of-state-for-exiting-the-european-union-v-wightman-and-others.pdf|title=Reasons for the determination in the matter of Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union (Appellant) v Wightman and others (Respondents)|last=UK Supreme Court|website=UK Supreme Court|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120221031/https://www.supremecourt.uk/docs/reasons-for-the-determination-in-the-matter-of-secretary-of-state-for-exiting-the-european-union-v-wightman-and-others.pdf|archive-date=20 November 2018|url-status=live|access-date=20 November 2018}}</ref> On 10 December 2018, the Court of Justice of the EU ruled that the UK could unilaterally revoke its Article 50 notification.<ref>{{cite web|title=The United Kingdom is free to revoke unilaterally the notification of its intention to withdraw from the EU.|url=https://curia.europa.eu/jcms/upload/docs/application/pdf/2018-12/cp180191en.pdf|publisher=Court of Justice of the European Union|access-date=18 January 2019|date=10 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190612165315/https://curia.europa.eu/jcms/upload/docs/application/pdf/2018-12/cp180191en.pdf|archive-date=12 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

==Impact==
{{redirect|Impact of Brexit|predicted impact|Predicted impact of Brexit}}
Many effects of Brexit depended on whether the UK left with a [[withdrawal agreement]], or before an agreement was ratified ([[No-deal Brexit|"no-deal" Brexit]]).<ref name="What is a 'no deal' Brexit?">{{cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/brexit/no-deal-brexit-what-meaning-uk-leave-uk-consequences/|title=What is a no-deal Brexit? Here are the consequences of the UK leaving the EU without a deal|date=4 September 2019|website=inews.co.uk|access-date=20 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610235916/https://inews.co.uk/news/brexit/no-deal-brexit-what-meaning-uk-leave-uk-consequences/|archive-date=10 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2017, the ''Financial Times'' said that there were approximately 759 international agreements, spanning 168 non-EU countries, that the UK would no longer be a party to upon leaving the EU.<ref name="FTAfter">{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/f1435a8e-372b-11e7-bce4-9023f8c0fd2e|title=After Brexit: the UK will need to renegotiate at least 759 treaties|last1=McClean|first1=Paul|date=30 May 2017|work=Financial Times|access-date=31 May 2017|quote=Through analysis of the EU treaty database, the FT found 759 separate EU bilateral agreements with potential relevance to Britain, covering trade in nuclear goods, customs, fisheries, trade, transport and regulatory co-operation in areas such as antitrust or financial services. This includes multilateral agreements based on consensus, where Britain must re-approach 132 separate parties. Around 110 separate opt-in accords at the UN and World Trade Organization are excluded from the estimates, as are narrow agreements on the environment, health, research and science. Some additional UK bilateral deals, outside the EU framework, may also need to be revised because they make reference to EU law. Some of the 759 are so essential that it would be unthinkable to operate without them. Air services agreements allow British aeroplanes to land in America, Canada or Israel; nuclear accords permit the trade in spare parts and fuel for Britain's power stations. Both these sectors are excluded from trade negotiations and must be addressed separately.|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531162500/https://www.ft.com/content/f1435a8e-372b-11e7-bce4-9023f8c0fd2e|archive-date=31 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Economic effects===
{{main|Economic effects of Brexit}}
Economists speculated that Brexit would have a damaging impact on the economies of the UK and at least part of the EU27. In particular, there was a broad consensus among economists, and in the economic literature, that Brexit would likely reduce the UK's real per capita income in the medium and long term, and that the Brexit referendum itself would damage the economy.<ref name="Sampson-2017" /><ref name="Giles-2017">{{cite news |last=Giles |first=Chris |title=Brexit will damage UK standards of living, say economists |url=https://www.ft.com/content/dc62922a-204b-11e7-a454-ab04428977f9 |url-status=live |website=[[Financial Times]] |date=16 April 2017 |access-date=22 November 2017 |quote=Unlike the short-term effects of Brexit, which have been better than most had predicted, most economists say the ultimate impact of leaving the EU still appears likely to be more negative than positive. But the one thing almost all agree upon is that no one will know how big the effects are for some time. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722161152/https://www.ft.com/content/dc62922a-204b-11e7-a454-ab04428977f9 |archive-date=22 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://piie.com/publications/working-papers/brexit-everyone-loses-britain-loses-most|title=Brexit: Everyone Loses, but Britain Loses the Most|date=1 March 2019|website=PIIE|access-date=17 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327091244/https://piie.com/publications/working-papers/brexit-everyone-loses-britain-loses-most|archive-date=27 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Studies found Brexit-induced uncertainty reduced British GDP, British national income, investment by business, employment and British international trade from June 2016 onwards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://voxeu.org/article/impact-brexit-uncertainty-uk-exports|title=The impact of Brexit uncertainty on UK exports|last1=Crowley|first1=Meredith|last2=Exton|first2=Oliver|date=21 January 2019|website=VoxEU.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708142203/https://voxeu.org/article/impact-brexit-uncertainty-uk-exports|archive-date=8 July 2019|access-date=21 January 2019|last3=Han|first3=Lu}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://theconversation.com/brexit-has-already-hurt-eu-and-non-eu-exports-by-up-to-13-new-research-105334|title=Brexit has already hurt EU and non-EU exports by up to 13% – new research|last=Soegaard|first=Christian|work=The Conversation|access-date=5 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105202912/https://theconversation.com/brexit-has-already-hurt-eu-and-non-eu-exports-by-up-to-13-new-research-105334|archive-date=5 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Douch|first1=Mustapha|last2=Edwards|first2=T. Huw|last3=Soegaard|first3=Christian|date=2018|title=The Trade Effects of the Brexit Announcement Shock|url=https://ideas.repec.org/p/wrk/warwec/1176.html|url-status=dead|journal=The Warwick Economics Research Paper Series (TWERPS)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181106004634/https://ideas.repec.org/p/wrk/warwec/1176.html|archive-date=6 November 2018|access-date=5 November 2018}}</ref>

A 2019 analysis found that British firms substantially increased [[offshoring]] to the EU after the Brexit referendum, whereas European firms reduced new investments in the UK.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Breinlich |first1=Holger |last2=Leromain |first2=Elsa |last3=Novy|first3=Dennis|last4=Sampson|first4=Thomas|url=https://voxeu.org/article/brexit-and-outward-investment-uk-firms |title=Voting with their money: Brexit and outward investment by UK firms|date=12 February 2019|website=VoxEU.org|access-date=13 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190212120115/https://voxeu.org/article/brexit-and-outward-investment-uk-firms |archive-date=12 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-eu-investment-idUKKCN1Q003D|title=Brexit referendum spurs British companies into investing in EU|date=11 February 2019 |publisher=Reuters |access-date=13 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190213124128/https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-eu-investment-idUKKCN1Q003D|archive-date=13 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The British government's Brexit analysis, leaked in January 2018, showed British economic growth would be stunted by 2–8% over the 15 years following Brexit, the amount depending on the leave scenario.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Government's Own Brexit Analysis Says The UK Will Be Worse Off in Every Scenario Outside The EU|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/albertonardelli/the-governments-own-brexit-analysis-says-the-uk-will-be|work=BuzzFeed|access-date=30 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180129235752/https://www.buzzfeed.com/albertonardelli/the-governments-own-brexit-analysis-says-the-uk-will-be|archive-date=29 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Parker |first=George |url=https://www.ft.com/content/b3d35136-0543-11e8-9650-9c0ad2d7c5b5|title=Secret data show Britain worse off under all Brexit scenarios|website=Financial Times|date=30 January 2018|access-date=30 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190904210201/https://www.ft.com/content/b3d35136-0543-11e8-9650-9c0ad2d7c5b5|archive-date=4 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Economists warned that London's future as an international financial centre depended on passport agreements with the EU.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Eichengreen|first=Barry|s2cid=159090073|date=7 January 2019|title=The international financial implications of Brexit|journal=International Economics and Economic Policy|volume=16|pages=37–50|doi=10.1007/s10368-018-0422-x|issn=1612-4812}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Armour|first=John|date=1 March 2017|title=Brexit and financial settrvices|journal=Oxford Review of Economic Policy|volume=33|issue=suppl_1|pages=S54–S69|doi=10.1093/oxrep/grx014|issn=0266-903X|doi-access=free}}</ref> Pro-Brexit activists and politicians have argued for negotiating trade and migration agreements with the "[[CANZUK]]" countries—those of [[Canada]], [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]] and the [[United Kingdom]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/09/13/canzuk-after-brexit-canada-australia-new-zealand-and-britain-can/|title=CANZUK: after Brexit, Canada, Australia, New Zealand and Britain can unite as a pillar of Western civilisation|author=Andrew Roberts|date=13 September 2016|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=3 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190114034026/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/09/13/canzuk-after-brexit-canada-australia-new-zealand-and-britain-can/|archive-date=14 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Bennett|first=James C.|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/columnist/2016/06/24/brexit-boosts-canzuk-replacement-european-union-column/86347818/|title=Brexit boosts 'CANZUK' replacement for European Union: Column|date=24 June 2016|work=USA Today|access-date=3 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725124317/https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/columnist/2016/06/24/brexit-boosts-canzuk-replacement-european-union-column/86347818/|archive-date=25 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>—but economists have said that trade deals with those countries would be far less valuable to the UK than EU membership.<ref>{{cite news|last=Krugman|first=Paul|author-link=Paul Krugman|title=Opinion {{!}} Brexit Meets Gravity|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/10/opinion/brexit-meets-gravity.html|url-status=live|work=The New York Times|date=10 July 2018|access-date=14 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190115023457/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/10/opinion/brexit-meets-gravity.html|archive-date=15 January 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.lse.ac.uk/brexit/2018/08/21/can-brexit-defy-gravity-right-now-it-is-still-much-cheaper-to-trade-with-neighbouring-countries/|title=Long read: Can Brexit defy gravity? It is still much cheaper to trade with neighbouring countries|date=21 August 2018|website=LSE BREXIT|language=en-US|access-date=14 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190115023228/http://blogs.lse.ac.uk/brexit/2018/08/21/can-brexit-defy-gravity-right-now-it-is-still-much-cheaper-to-trade-with-neighbouring-countries/|archive-date=15 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://voxeu.org/article/how-economists-brexit-manage-defy-laws-gravity|title=How 'Economists for Brexit' manage to defy the laws of gravity|last1=Sampson|first1=Thomas|last2=Dhingra|first2=Swati|date=2 June 2016|website=VoxEU.org|access-date=14 January 2019|last3=Ottaviano|first3=Gianmarco|last4=Reenen|first4=John Van|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190115023300/https://voxeu.org/article/how-economists-brexit-manage-defy-laws-gravity|archive-date=15 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Studies projected that Brexit would exacerbate regional economic inequality in the UK, by hitting already-struggling regions the hardest.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Carter|first1=Andrew|last2=Swinney|first2=Paul|year=2019|title=Brexit and the Future of the UK's Unbalanced Economic Geography|journal=The Political Quarterly|volume=90|pages=72–83|doi=10.1111/1467-923X.12649|issn=1467-923X|quote=What all of these studies agree on is that whichever Brexit deal is struck, even the most advantageous will have a negative impact on future economic growth for all places across the UK in the short to medium term. And they also agree that over the longer term its places that are already struggling that are likely to struggle the most, further exacerbating the country's unbalanced economic geography.|doi-access=free}}</ref>

===Local and geographic effects===
{{main|Post-Brexit United Kingdom relations with the European Union}}
[[File:The Border on Killeen School Road - geograph.org.uk - 446719.jpg|thumb|Border crossing at Killeen (near [[Newry]] in [[Northern Ireland]]), marked only by a speed limit in km/h (Northern Ireland uses mph.)]]
The potential [[Brexit and the Irish border|impact on the border]] between [[Northern Ireland]] and the [[Republic of Ireland]] has been a contentious issue. Since 2005, [[Republic of Ireland–United Kingdom border|the border]] had been essentially invisible.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channel4.com/news/factcheck/factcheck-what-are-the-options-for-the-irish-border-after-brexit|title=FactCheck: What are the options for the Irish border after Brexit?|work=Channel4.com|date=29 November 2017|access-date=25 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180914121956/https://www.channel4.com/news/factcheck/factcheck-what-are-the-options-for-the-irish-border-after-brexit|archive-date=14 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> After Brexit, it became the only UK–EU land border<ref>{{cite news|title=Brexit will not mean hard border, leaders vow|url-access=registration|date=31 January 2017|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/brexit-will-not-mean-hard-border-leaders-vow-83c7lzs80|work=[[The Times, Ireland edition]]|first=Niamh|last=Lyons|access-date=29 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131070359/http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/brexit-will-not-mean-hard-border-leaders-vow-83c7lzs80|archive-date=31 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> (not counting the land borders that EU states Spain and Cyprus have with [[British Overseas Territories]]). All involved parties agreed a hard border should be avoided,<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Irish Times|date=26 July 2016|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/uk/brexit-may-not-impact-common-travel-area-expert-claims-1.2711557|access-date=12 October 2016|title=Britain does not want return to Northern Ireland border controls, says May|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012155040/http://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/uk/brexit-may-not-impact-common-travel-area-expert-claims-1.2711557|archive-date=12 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> for it might compromise the [[Good Friday Agreement]] that ended the [[Northern Ireland conflict]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Robertson |first=Nic |title=Brexit: the unexpected threat to peace in Northern Ireland |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/04/06/opinions/20-years-good-friday-agreement-northern-ireland-nic-r-intl/index.html |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=6 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614050104/https://edition.cnn.com/2018/04/06/opinions/20-years-good-friday-agreement-northern-ireland-nic-r-intl/index.html |archive-date=14 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/george-mitchell-uk-and-ireland-need-to-realise-whats-at-stake-in-brexit-talks-36785893.html |title=George Mitchell: UK and Ireland need to realise what's at stake in Brexit talks |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329172607/https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/george-mitchell-uk-and-ireland-need-to-realise-whats-at-stake-in-brexit-talks-36785893.html |archive-date=29 March 2019 |work=[[Belfast Telegraph]] |date=8 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=David |title=Brexit threatens Good Friday agreement, Irish PM warns |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/mar/14/brexit-threatens-good-friday-agreement-irish-pm-warns |work=The Guardian |date=14 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731012207/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/mar/14/brexit-threatens-good-friday-agreement-irish-pm-warns |archive-date=31 July 2018}}</ref> To forestall this, the EU proposed a [[Irish backstop|"backstop agreement"]] that would have kept the UK in the Customs Union and kept Northern Ireland in some aspects of the Single Market also, until a lasting solution was found.<ref name="BBC backstop">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-politics-44615404|title=Brexit: What are the backstop options?|work=BBC News|date=13 September 2019|access-date=24 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725040206/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-politics-44615404|archive-date=25 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The UK Parliament rejected this proposal. After [[Brexit negotiations in 2019|further negotiations in autumn of 2019]], an alternative model, the [[Northern Ireland Protocol|Ireland/Northern Ireland Protocol]] was agreed between the UK and the EU. Under the Protocol, Northern Ireland is formally outside the EU single market, but [[European Single Market|EU free movement of goods]] rules and [[EU Customs Union]] rules still apply; this ensures there are no customs checks or controls between Northern Ireland and the rest of the island. In place of an Ireland/Northern Ireland land border, the protocol has created a {{lang|la|[[de facto]]}} customs "[[Irish Sea border]]" for goods from (but not to) Great Britain,<ref name="bbcNewDeal">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-50083026|title=Brexit: What is in Boris Johnson's new deal with the EU?|website=BBC News|date=21 October 2019|access-date=2 January 2020|archive-date=22 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222170733/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-50083026|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="FTNewDeal">{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/cdb2dadc-ec40-11e9-a240-3b065ef5fc55|title=How Boris Johnson moved to break the Brexit deadlock|website=Financial Times|date=11 October 2019|access-date=2 January 2020|last1=Parker|first1=George|last2=Brunsden|first2=Jim|url-access=subscription|archive-date=7 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191207163635/https://www.ft.com/content/cdb2dadc-ec40-11e9-a240-3b065ef5fc55|url-status=live}}</ref> to the disquiet of prominent [[Ulster Unionism|Unionists]].<ref>{{cite news |date=7 May 2021 |title=Good Friday Agreement negotiators call for NI Protocol suspension |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-57030871 |access-date=10 March 2022 |archive-date=11 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230111135248/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-57030871 |url-status=live }}</ref>

After the Brexit referendum, the [[Scottish Government]]&nbsp;– led by the [[Scottish National Party]] (SNP)&nbsp;– planned [[Proposed second Scottish independence referendum|another independence referendum]] because Scotland voted to remain in the EU while England and Wales voted to leave.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/25/world/europe/brexit-scotland-independence-referendum.html|title=Scotland Says New Vote on Independence Is 'Highly Likely'|date=25 June 2016|work=The New York Times|access-date=17 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216050257/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/25/world/europe/brexit-scotland-independence-referendum.html|archive-date=16 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> It had suggested this before the Brexit referendum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2016/01/24/nicola-sturgeon-denies-she-has-machiavellian-wish-for-brexit_n_9063372.html|title=Nicola Sturgeon Denies She Has "Machiavellian" Wish For Brexit|last=Simons|first=Ned|date=24 January 2016|website=The Huffington Post UK|access-date=3 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203234636/http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2016/01/24/nicola-sturgeon-denies-she-has-machiavellian-wish-for-brexit_n_9063372.html|archive-date=3 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[First Minister of Scotland]], [[Nicola Sturgeon]], requested a referendum be held before the UK's withdrawal,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/nicola-sturgeon-scottish-independence-referendum-eu-membership-back-of-queue-spain-a7638101.html |title=Nicola Sturgeon says Scotland will pursue EU membership after independence |work=The Independent |date=20 March 2017 |access-date=20 March 2017 |archive-date=28 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190428213622/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/nicola-sturgeon-scottish-independence-referendum-eu-membership-back-of-queue-spain-a7638101.html |url-status=live }}</ref> but the British Prime Minister rejected this timing, but not the referendum itself.<ref>{{cite news|last=Stewart|first=Heather|date=16 March 2017|title=Theresa May rejects Nicola Sturgeon's referendum demand|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/mar/16/theresa-may-rejects-nicola-sturgeons-scottish-referendum-demand|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=15 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531114753/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/mar/16/theresa-may-rejects-nicola-sturgeons-scottish-referendum-demand|archive-date=31 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> At the referendum in 2014, 55% of voters had decided to remain in the UK, but the referendum on Britain's withdrawal from the EU was held in 2016, with 62% of Scottish voters against it. In March 2017, the Scottish Parliament voted in favour of holding another independence referendum. Sturgeon called for a "phased return" of an independent Scotland back to the EU.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/may/14/sturgeon-independent-scotland-may-need-phased-return-to-eu |title=Sturgeon: independent Scotland may need "phased" return to EU |date=14 May 2017 |newspaper=The Guardian |access-date=15 May 2017 |archive-date=18 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190518142806/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/may/14/sturgeon-independent-scotland-may-need-phased-return-to-eu |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2017, if Northern Ireland remained associated with the EU – for example, by remaining in the Customs Union, some analysts argued Scotland would also insist on special treatment.<ref name="Brexit-Reuters-04122017">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-deals/scotland-wales-and-london-want-special-brexit-deal-if-northern-ireland-gets-one-idUSKBN1DY24L|title=Scotland, Wales and London want special Brexit deal if Northern Ireland gets one|date=4 December 2017|publisher=Reuters|access-date=8 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191008152318/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-deals/scotland-wales-and-london-want-special-brexit-deal-if-northern-ireland-gets-one-idUSKBN1DY24L|archive-date=8 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> However, in the event, the only part of the United Kingdom which received unique treatment was Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite news|date=15 March 2021|title=Brexit: What is the Northern Ireland Protocol and why are there checks?|language=en-GB|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/explainers-53724381|access-date=21 April 2021|archive-date=20 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210420123453/https://www.bbc.com/news/explainers-53724381|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 21 March 2018, the Scottish Parliament passed the [[UK Withdrawal from the European Union (Legal Continuity) (Scotland) Bill 2018|Scottish Continuity Bill]].<ref name="Herald Scotland">{{cite news |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/16110743.Whitehall_lawyers_drawing_up_plans_to_challenge_Continuity_Bill_in_courts/ |title=Whitehall lawyers drawing up plans to challenge Continuity Bill in courts |work=Herald Scotland |date=2018 |access-date=3 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180403175132/http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/16110743.Whitehall_lawyers_drawing_up_plans_to_challenge_Continuity_Bill_in_courts/|archive-date=3 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> This was passed due to stalling negotiations between the Scottish Government and the British Government on where powers within devolved policy areas should lie after Brexit. The Act allowed for all devolved policy areas to remain within the remit of the Scottish Parliament and reduces the executive power upon exit day that the UK Withdrawal Bill provides for Ministers of the Crown.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.lse.ac.uk/businessreview/2018/03/17/forging-a-new-uk-wide-agricultural-framework-post-brexit/|title=Forging a new UK-wide agricultural framework post-Brexit |publisher=LSE|date=2018|access-date=3 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180403173752/http://blogs.lse.ac.uk/businessreview/2018/03/17/forging-a-new-uk-wide-agricultural-framework-post-brexit/|archive-date=3 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The bill was referred to the UK Supreme Court, which found that it could not come into force as the [[European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018]], which received royal assent between the Scottish Parliament passing its bill and the Supreme Court's judgement, designated itself under schedule{{nbsp}}4 of the [[Scotland Act 1998]] as unamendable by the Scottish Parliament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2018/16/schedule/3/paragraph/21/enacted/data.htm|title=European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018|website=www.legislation.gov.uk|access-date=6 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806182954/http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2018/16/schedule/3/paragraph/21/enacted/data.htm|archive-date=6 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The bill has therefore not received royal assent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.holyrood.com/articles/news/eu-continuity-bill-was-within-competence-scottish-parliament-when-it-was-passed|title=EU Continuity Bill was within competence of Scottish Parliament when it was passed|date=13 December 2018|website=Holyrood Magazine|access-date=6 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806112407/https://www.holyrood.com/articles/news/eu-continuity-bill-was-within-competence-scottish-parliament-when-it-was-passed|archive-date=6 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[File:Gibraltar Customs side of the Spain-Gibraltar frontier, Winston Churchill Avenue, Gibraltar.jpg|thumb|Cars crossing into [[Gibraltar]] from [[Spain]] clearing customs formalities. Gibraltar is outside the customs union, VAT area, and [[Schengen Zone]].]]
[[Gibraltar]], a [[British Overseas Territory]] bordering Spain, is [[Effect of Brexit on Gibraltar|affected by Brexit]] too. Spain asserts a [[Status of Gibraltar|territorial claim on Gibraltar]]. After the referendum, Spain's Foreign Minister renewed calls for joint Spanish–British control.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-36618796|title=Brexit: Spain calls for joint control of Gibraltar|work=BBC News|access-date=26 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626055917/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-36618796|archive-date=26 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In late 2018, the British and Spanish governments agreed that any dispute over Gibraltar would not affect Brexit negotiations,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/world/uk-spain-reach-brexit-deal-over-gibraltar-spanish-pm/article/534934 |title=UK, Spain reach Brexit deal over Gibraltar: Spanish PM|date=18 October 2018|work=Digital Journal|access-date=12 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328153315/http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/world/uk-spain-reach-brexit-deal-over-gibraltar-spanish-pm/article/534934|archive-date=28 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and the British government agreed that UK–EU treaties made after Brexit would not automatically apply to Gibraltar.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/europe/spanish-pm-lifts-effective-veto-on-brexit-deal-after-gibraltar-guarantee-1.3709604 |title=Spanish PM lifts effective veto on Brexit deal after Gibraltar 'guarantee' |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125152747/https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/europe/spanish-pm-lifts-effective-veto-on-brexit-deal-after-gibraltar-guarantee-1.3709604 |archive-date=25 November 2018 |newspaper=The Irish Times |date=24 November 2018}}</ref> In December 2020, Spain and the UK reached an [[Effect of Brexit on Gibraltar#Post-Brexit|agreement in principle on future arrangements]] for Brexit and invited the European Commission to formalise it as a treaty.

The French and British governments say they remain committed to the [[Le Touquet Agreement]], which lets UK border checks be completed in France, and vice versa ([[juxtaposed controls]]).<ref name="French border">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-42723401 "Calais migrants: UK and France sign new treaty"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220309220655/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-42723401 |date=9 March 2022 }}. BBC News. 19 January 2018.</ref> The two governments signed the Sandhurst Treaty in January 2018, which will shorten the time taken to process [[Migrants around Calais|migrants attempting to reach the UK]] from [[Calais]], from six months to one month. The UK also announced it will invest a further £44.5 million on border security at the English Channel.<ref name="French border" />

===Effects on the European Union===
{{main|Impact of Brexit on the European Union}}
Brexit [[Impact of Brexit on the European Union|caused the European Union]] to lose its second-largest economy, its third-most populous country,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merkur.de/politik/brexit-folgen-fuer-deutschland-und-eu-zr-6489983.html|title=EU-Austritt des UK: Diese Folgen hat der Brexit für Deutschland und die EU|date=22 August 2016|work=[[Merkur.de]]|language=de|trans-title=UK Exit from EU: Brexit has these consequences for Germany and the EU|access-date=30 November 2016|quote=Die Briten haben sich für einen Abschied entschieden, Europa wird nun anders aussehen. Der Kontinent verliert seine (neben Frankreich) stärkste Militärmacht samt Atomwaffenarsenal, seine zweitgrößte Volkswirtschaft, das Land mit der drittgrößten Bevölkerung, die Finanzhauptstadt der Welt und einen von zwei Plätzen im UN-Sicherheitsrat. [The British have decided to leave. Europe will now look different. The continent will be losing its strongest military power (alongside France),{{nbsp}}... its second largest economy, the country with the third largest population, the financial capital of the world, and one of two seats on the UN Security Council.]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161209172124/http://www.merkur.de/politik/brexit-folgen-fuer-deutschland-und-eu-zr-6489983.html|archive-date=9 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> and the second-largest net contributor to the EU budget.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.faz.net/aktuell/wirtschaft/eurokrise/deutschland-zahlt-am-meisten-in-den-eu-haushalt-14378202.html|title=EU-Haushalt: Deutschland überweist das meiste Geld an Brüssel|last=Hendrik Kafsack|date=8 August 2016|work=Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung|access-date=9 October 2016|language=de|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161009105442/https://www.faz.net/aktuell/wirtschaft/eurokrise/deutschland-zahlt-am-meisten-in-den-eu-haushalt-14378202.html|archive-date=9 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>

The UK is no longer a shareholder in the [[European Investment Bank]], where it had 16% of the shares.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.faz.net/aktuell/wirtschaft/wirtschaftspolitik/nettozahler-zum-eu-haushalt-brexit-wird-teuer-fuer-deutschland-14429116.html|title=Brexit wird teuer für Deutschland|publisher=Reuters/[[Deutsche Presse-Agentur]]|date=10 September 2016|work=Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung|access-date=9 October 2016|language=de|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161009105443/https://www.faz.net/aktuell/wirtschaft/wirtschaftspolitik/nettozahler-zum-eu-haushalt-brexit-wird-teuer-fuer-deutschland-14429116.html|archive-date=9 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The European Investment Bank's Board of Governors decided that the remaining member states would proportionally increase their capital subscriptions to maintain the same level of overall subscribed capital (EUR 243.3 billion).<ref>{{cite web|title=EIB President regrets Brexit and welcomes EU 27 united support for EIB Group|url=https://www.eib.org/en/press/news/eib-president-regrets-brexit-welcomes-eu27-united-support-for-eib-group|access-date=28 April 2021|website=European Investment Bank|archive-date=28 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210428105400/https://www.eib.org/en/press/news/eib-president-regrets-brexit-welcomes-eu27-united-support-for-eib-group|url-status=live}}</ref> As of March 2020, the subscribed capital of the EIB had increased by an additional EUR 5.5 billion, following the decision by two member states to increase their capital subscriptions ([[Poland]] and [[Romania]]). The EIB's total subscribed capital thus amounted to EUR 248.8 billion. Brexit did not impact the EIB Group's AAA credit rating.<ref>{{cite web |title=EU member states avert €100bn Brexit 'disaster' for European Investment Bank |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/brexit-european-investment-bank-disaster-hoyer-a9310936.html |website=The Independent |date=31 January 2020 |access-date=28 April 2021 |archive-date=28 April 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210428103852/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/brexit-european-investment-bank-disaster-hoyer-a9310936.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

Analyses indicated that the departure of the relatively economically liberal UK would reduce the ability of remaining economically liberal countries to block measures in the [[Council of the EU]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Huhe|first1=Narisong|last2=Naurin|first2=Daniel|last3=Thomson|first3=Robert|s2cid=211381583|title=Don't cry for me Britannia: The resilience of the European Union to Brexit|journal=European Union Politics|volume=21|page=1465116519882096|doi=10.1177/1465116519882096|issn=1465-1165|url=https://strathprints.strath.ac.uk/69935/1/Huhe_etal_EUP_2019_the_resilience_of_the_European_Union_to_Brexit.pdf|year=2020|hdl=10852/76151|access-date=30 January 2020|archive-date=24 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224142252/https://strathprints.strath.ac.uk/69935/1/Huhe_etal_EUP_2019_the_resilience_of_the_European_Union_to_Brexit.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://carnegieeurope.eu/2018/03/23/there-is-life-for-eu-after-brexit-pub-75876|title=There Is Life for the EU After Brexit|last=Gruyter|first=Caroline de|website=Carnegie Europe|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205060756/https://carnegieeurope.eu/2018/03/23/there-is-life-for-eu-after-brexit-pub-75876|archive-date=5 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2019, ahead of Brexit, the [[European Medicines Agency]] and [[European Banking Authority]] moved their headquarters from London to [[Amsterdam]] and [[Paris]], respectively.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/news/ema-now-operating-amsterdam|title=EMA now operating from Amsterdam|publisher=European Medicines Agency|date=11 March 2019|access-date=3 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016015945/https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/news/ema-now-operating-amsterdam|archive-date=16 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thepharmaletter.com/article/ema-gets-keys-to-new-hq|work=[[The Pharma Letter]]|date=18 November 2019|title=EMA gets keys to new HQ|access-date=3 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203032720/https://www.thepharmaletter.com/article/ema-gets-keys-to-new-hq|archive-date=3 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thelocal.fr/20190605/european-bank-regulator-arrives-in-paris-in-boost-to-macrons-financial-vision-for-city|title=European bank regulator arrives in Paris in boost to Macron's financial vision for city|date=5 June 2019|work=The Local|access-date=3 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203032718/https://www.thelocal.fr/20190605/european-bank-regulator-arrives-in-paris-in-boost-to-macrons-financial-vision-for-city|archive-date=3 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Sectorial effects===
The UK has left the [[Common Agricultural Policy]] (CAP),<ref name="CAP payments">{{cite web|first1=Fergal |last1=Davis |first2=Jonathan |last2=Finlay |first3=Sarah |last3=Coe |url=https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/farm-payments-in-a-no-deal-brexit/ |title=Farm payments in a no-deal Brexit |publisher=House of Commons Library |website=commonslibrary.parliament.uk |date=18 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211121150326/https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/farm-payments-in-a-no-deal-brexit/ |archive-date=21 November 2021 |url-status=live}}</ref> which provides government financial support to farmers in the EU.<ref name="CAP">{{cite web |url=https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/explainers/common-agricultural-policy |title=Common Agricultural Policy |date=16 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190906173554/https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/explainers/common-agricultural-policy |archive-date=6 September 2019 |publisher=[[Institute for Government]]}}</ref> Brexit allowed the UK to develop its own agriculture policy<ref name="UK agriculture policy">{{cite web|first1=Emma |last1=Downing |first2=Lukas |last2=Audickas |first3=Sarah |last3=Coe |url=https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/research-briefings/cbp-8218/ |title=Brexit: UK agriculture policy |publisher=House of Commons Library |website=commonslibrary.parliament.uk |type=Research briefing |date=11 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210225001241/https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/research-briefings/cbp-8218/ |archive-date=25 February 2021 |url-status=live}}</ref> and the [[Agriculture Act 2020]] replaced the CAP with a new system.<ref name="Agriculture Act 2020">{{Cite web|url=https://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2020/21/contents/enacted|title=Agriculture Act 2020}}</ref> The UK did also leave the [[Common Fisheries Policy]] (CFP)<ref name="fisheries briefing">{{cite web|first1=Elena |last1=Ares |date=30 October 2019 |url=https://researchbriefings.files.parliament.uk/documents/CBP-8396/CBP-8396.pdf |title=Fisheries and Brexit |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211009121948/https://researchbriefings.files.parliament.uk/documents/CBP-8396/CBP-8396.pdf |archive-date=9 October 2021 |url-status=live |type=Briefing paper |publisher=House of Commons Library |website=researchbriefings.files.parliament.uk |id=Number 8396 |page=4}}</ref> that lets all EU countries fish within 12 nautical miles of the British coast<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-36358016 |title=Reality Check: How would Brexit affect the UK's fishing waters? |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001015505/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-36358016 |archive-date=1 October 2019 |work=BBC News |date=31 May 2016}}</ref> and lets the EU set catch quotas.<ref name="CFP explainer">{{cite web |url=https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/explainers/common-fisheries-policy |title=Common Fisheries Policy |date=17 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190518094241/https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/explainers/common-fisheries-policy |archive-date=18 May 2019 |publisher=Institute for Government}}</ref> The combined EU fishing fleets landed about six million tonnes of fish per year, as of 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/fisheries/documentation/publications/pcp_en.pdf |title=Main world producers (2007) |access-date=23 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812111024/http://ec.europa.eu/fisheries/documentation/publications/pcp_en.pdf |archive-date=12 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> about half of which were from British waters.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/feb/15/uk-fishermen-may-not-win-waters-back-after-brexit-eu-memo-reveals|title=UK fishermen may not win waters back after Brexit, EU memo reveals|author=Daniel Boffey|date=15 February 2017|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=3 July 2017|location=London|quote=Source: House of Lords, NAFC Marine Centre, University of the Highlands and Islands.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170702131533/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/feb/15/uk-fishermen-may-not-win-waters-back-after-brexit-eu-memo-reveals|archive-date=2 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> By leaving the CFP, the UK could develop its own fisheries policy.<ref name="CFP explainer" /> The UK did also leave the [[London Fisheries Convention]] that lets Irish, French, Belgian, Dutch and German vessels fish within six nautical miles of the UK's coast.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40471466 |title=UK to withdraw from international fishing arrangement |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190910072536/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40471466 |archive-date=10 September 2019 |work=BBC News |date=2 July 2017}}</ref>

Brexit poses challenges to British academia and research, as the UK loses research funding from EU sources and sees a reduction in students from the EU. Academic institutions find it harder to hire researchers from the EU and British students will face greater difficulties with studying abroad in the EU.<ref name="Mayhew-2017">{{Cite journal|last=Mayhew|first=Ken|date=1 March 2017|title=UK higher education and Brexit|journal=Oxford Review of Economic Policy|volume=33|issue=suppl_1|pages=S155–S161|doi=10.1093/oxrep/grx012|issn=0266-903X|doi-access=free}}</ref> The UK was a member of the [[European Research Area]] and likely to wish to remain an associated member following Brexit.<ref>"It is likely that the UK would wish to remain an associated member of the European Research Area, like Norway and Iceland, in order to continue participating in the EU framework programmes."{{Cite book|url=http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0023/002354/235406e.pdf|title=UNESCO Science Report: towards 2030|publisher=UNESCO Publishing|year=2015|isbn=978-92-3-100129-1|location=Paris|page=269|access-date=20 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170630025557/http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0023/002354/235406e.pdf|archive-date=30 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The British government has guaranteed funding for research currently funded by EU.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/aug/13/philip-hammond-treasury-to-guarantee-post-brexit-funding-for-eu-backed-projects|title=Treasury to guarantee post-Brexit funding for EU-backed projects|first1=Jessica|last1=Elgot|first2=Larry|last2=Elliott|first3=Nicola|last3=Davis|date=13 August 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=14 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170414164358/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/aug/13/philip-hammond-treasury-to-guarantee-post-brexit-funding-for-eu-backed-projects|archive-date=14 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>

An early 2019 study found that Brexit would deplete the [[National Health Service]] (NHS) workforce, create uncertainties regarding care for British nationals living in the EU, and put at risk access to vaccines, equipment, and medicines.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=McKee|first1=Martin|last2=Galsworthy|first2=Mike|last3=Stuckler|first3=David|last4=Jarman|first4=Holly|last5=Greer|first5=Scott|last6=Hervey|first6=Tamara|last7=Fahy|first7=Nick|s2cid=72334219|date=25 February 2019|title=How will Brexit affect health services in the UK? An updated evaluation|journal=The Lancet|volume=393|issue=10174|pages=949–958|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(19)30425-8|issn=0140-6736|pmid=30819519|url=http://eprints.whiterose.ac.uk/160321/3/Lancet%202019%20clean%20as%20submitted.pdf}}</ref> The [[Department of Health and Social Care]] has said it has taken steps to ensure the continuity of medical supplies after Brexit.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/eu-exit/medicines/ |title=Continuity of supplies |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191212005859/https://www.england.nhs.uk/eu-exit/medicines/ |archive-date=12 December 2019 |publisher= [[NHS England]]}}</ref> The number of non-British EU nurses registering with the NHS fell from 1,304 in July 2016 to 46 in April 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2017/jun/12/96-drop-in-eu-nurses-registering-to-work-in-britain-since-brexit-vote|title=96% drop in EU nurses registering to work in Britain since Brexit vote|last=Siddique|first=Haroon|date=12 June 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=1 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402084706/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2017/jun/12/96-drop-in-eu-nurses-registering-to-work-in-britain-since-brexit-vote|archive-date=2 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>{{needs update|date=December 2021}}In June 2016, 58,702 NHS staff recorded a non-British EU nationality, and in June 2022, 70,735 NHS staff recorded an EU nationality. However, "to present this as the full story would be misleading, because there are over 57,000 more staff for whom nationality is known now than in 2016"<ref>{{Cite web |last=Baker |first=Carl |date=22 November 2022 |title=NHS staff from overseas: statistics |url=https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/research-briefings/cbp-7783/#:~:text=Between%20them%2C%20these%20staff%20hold,is%20correct%20at%20June%202022. |website=commonslibrary.parliament.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=NHS Workforce Statistics – June 2022 (Including selected provisional statistics for July 2022) |url=https://digital.nhs.uk/data-and-information/publications/statistical/nhs-workforce-statistics/june-2022 |access-date=20 January 2023 |website=NDRS |language=en}}</ref>

Under the [[European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018]], EU laws will no longer have [[Primacy of European Union law|supremacy over]] British laws after Brexit.<ref name="withdrawal bill">{{cite web |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2018/16/pdfs/ukpgaen_20180016_en.pdf |title=Explanatory notes on the European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190930205726/http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2018/16/pdfs/ukpgaen_20180016_en.pdf |archive-date=30 September 2019 |publisher= [[The Stationery Office]] |pages=4, 8}}</ref> To maintain continuity, the Act converts EU law into British law as "retained EU law". After Brexit, the British parliament (and the devolved legislatures) can decide which elements of that law to keep, amend or repeal.<ref name="withdrawal bill"/> Furthermore, British courts will no longer be bound by the judgments of the [[EU Court of Justice]] after Brexit.

After Brexit, the UK is able to control immigration from the EU and [[European Economic Area|EEA]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/publications/managing-migration-after-brexit |title=Managing migration after Brexit |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190929223849/https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/publications/managing-migration-after-brexit |archive-date=29 September 2019 |publisher=Institute for Government |date=8 March 2019|last1=Owen |first1=Joe |last2=Jack |first2=Maddy Thimont |last3=Iacobov |first3=Adela |last4=Christensen |first4=Elliott }}</ref> as it can end EU [[freedom of movement]]. The current British government intends to replace it with a new system{{update after|2020}} The government's 2018 [[white paper]] proposes a "skills-based immigration system" that prioritises skilled migrants. EU and EEA citizens already living in the UK can continue living there after Brexit by applying to the EU Settlement Scheme, which began in March 2019. Irish citizens will not have to apply to the scheme.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/dec/19/the-post-brexit-immigration-plans-at-a-glance |title=The post-Brexit immigration plans at a glance |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726214731/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/dec/19/the-post-brexit-immigration-plans-at-a-glance |archive-date=26 July 2019 |work=The Guardian|date=19 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first1=Hannah |last1=Wilkins |first2=Melissa |last2=Macdonald |first3=Neil |last3=Johnston |first4=Steven |last4=Kennedy |first5=Susan |last5=Hubble |first6=Tom |last6=Powell |url=https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/research-briefings/cbp-8584/ |title=EU Settlement Scheme |publisher=House of Commons Library |website=commonslibrary.parliament.uk |type=Research briefing |date=25 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210608103015/https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/research-briefings/cbp-8584/ |archive-date=8 June 2021 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-uks-future-skills-based-immigration-system/future-skills-based-immigration-system-executive-summary |title=Future skills-based immigration system: executive summary |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190929223835/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-uks-future-skills-based-immigration-system/future-skills-based-immigration-system-executive-summary |archive-date=29 September 2019 |publisher=[[Home Office]] |date=19 December 2018}}</ref> Studies estimate that Brexit and the end of free movement will likely result in a large decline in immigration from EEA countries to the UK.<ref name="immigration decline">{{cite report |last1=Forte |first1=Giuseppe |last2=Portes |first2=Jonathan |date=1 May 2017|title=Macroeconomic Determinants of International Migration to the UK|location=Rochester, NY |ssrn=2979949}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Portes|first=Jonathan|date=1 November 2016|title=Immigration after Brexit|journal=National Institute Economic Review|volume=238|issue=1|pages=R13–R21 |s2cid=157228784|issn=0027-9501 |doi=10.1177/002795011623800111}}</ref> After Brexit, any foreigner wanting to do so more than temporarily would need a work permit.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/46038799|title=Brexit: What effect could leaving the European Union have on football transfers?|date=31 October 2018|work=BBC Sport|access-date=11 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190112051235/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/46038799|archive-date=12 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/how-brexit-will-affect-premier-league-football/cwp6p3hhmuxx119cm1syhwyi2|title=How Brexit will affect Premier League football|date=22 March 2019|website=Goal.com|access-date=11 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190112145957/https://www.goal.com/en/news/how-brexit-will-affect-premier-league-football/cwp6p3hhmuxx119cm1syhwyi2|archive-date=12 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

By leaving the EU, the UK would leave the [[European Common Aviation Area]] (ECAA), a [[single market]] in commercial air travel,<ref name="Aviation-IFG">{{cite web |url=https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/explainers/european-common-aviation-area-brexit |title=Aviation and the European Common Aviation Area (ECAA) |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190930210000/https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/explainers/european-common-aviation-area-brexit |archive-date=30 September 2019 |publisher=Institute for Government |date=10 September 2017}}</ref> but could negotiate a number of different future relationships with the EU.<ref name="Aviation-IFG" /> British airlines would still have permission to operate within the EU with no restrictions, and vice versa. The British government seeks continued participation in the [[European Aviation Safety Agency]] (EASA).<ref name="Aviation-IFG" /> The UK has its own [[Air transport agreement|air service agreements]] with 111 countries, which permit flights to-and-from the country, and further 17 countries through its EU membership.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/flights-to-and-from-the-uk-if-theres-no-brexit-deal/flights-to-and-from-the-uk-if-theres-no-brexit-deal|title=Flights to and from the UK if there's no Brexit deal|date=24 September 2018|work=Government of the United Kingdom|access-date=9 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210152535/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/flights-to-and-from-the-uk-if-theres-no-brexit-deal/flights-to-and-from-the-uk-if-theres-no-brexit-deal|archive-date=10 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> These have since been replaced. Ferries will continue, but with obstacles such as customs checks.<ref name="atclogistics">{{cite web|url=https://www.atc-logistics.ie/getting-to-europe-post-brexit-the-impact-on-ferry-companies/|title=Getting to Europe Post Brexit – The Impact on Ferry Companies|date=23 April 2018|website=Atc-logistics.ie|access-date=22 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323004211/https://www.atc-logistics.ie/getting-to-europe-post-brexit-the-impact-on-ferry-companies/|archive-date=23 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> New ferry departures between the Republic of Ireland and the European mainland have been established.<ref name="atclogistics" /> {{As of|2020|08}}, the government's [[Goods Vehicle Movement Service]], an IT system essential to post-Brexit goods movements, was still only in the early stages of beta testing, with four months to go before it is required to be in operation.<ref>{{cite news|date=27 August 2020|title=U.K. Starts Research on Brexit Customs System Due in Four Months|work=Bloomberg.com|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-08-27/u-k-starts-research-on-brexit-customs-system-due-in-four-months|access-date=29 August 2020}}</ref>

Concerns were raised by European lawmakers, including [[Michel Barnier]], that Brexit might create security problems for the UK given that its law enforcement and counter-terrorism forces would no longer have access to the EU's security databases.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/why-brexit-may-be-good-for-terrorists-and-the-kremlin-and-bad-for-european-security/2018/12/24/b3ec2462-020a-11e9-958c-0a601226ff6b_story.html|title=Why Brexit may be good for terrorists and the Kremlin and bad for European security|date=2018|newspaper=The Washington Post|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190115234413/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/why-brexit-may-be-good-for-terrorists-and-the-kremlin-and-bad-for-european-security/2018/12/24/b3ec2462-020a-11e9-958c-0a601226ff6b_story.html|archive-date=15 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

Some analysts have suggested that the severe [[Economic impact of the COVID-19 pandemic in the United Kingdom|economic impact of the COVID-19 pandemic in the UK]] has masked the economic impact of Brexit in 2021.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Giles|first=Chris|date=1 July 2021|title=Covid pandemic masks Brexit impact on UK economy|work=Financial Times|url=https://www.ft.com/content/fbb70741-34cc-4f54-a66b-a2e4b9445f5b|access-date=13 October 2021}}</ref> In December 2021, the ''Financial Times'' quoted a range of economists as saying that the economic impact of Brexit on the UK economy and living standards "appears to be negative but uncertain".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Giles|first=Chris|date=23 December 2021|title=Brexit one year on: the impact on the UK economy|work=Financial Times|url=https://www.ft.com/content/c6ee4ce2-95b3-4d92-858f-c50566529b5e|access-date=31 December 2021}}</ref> According to the [[Office for Budget Responsibility]], the new trade agreement between the EU and UK could, over time, result in a 4% reduction in British productivity, compared with its level had the 2016 EU referendum gone the other way.<ref>{{cite news |title=The initial impact of Brexit on UK trade with the EU |url=https://obr.uk/box/the-initial-impact-of-brexit-on-uk-trade-with-the-eu/ |work=Office for Budget Responsibility |date=27 October 2021 |access-date=15 January 2022}}</ref>

Brexit was widely described as a factor contributing to the [[2021 United Kingdom natural gas supplier crisis]], in which [[2021 United Kingdom fuel supply crisis|panic buying]] led to serious disruption of road fuel supplies across the UK, as it exacerbated the UK's shortage of [[Heavy goods vehicle|HGV]] drivers.<ref>{{cite web|date=28 September 2021|title=Brexit has been a 'factor' in fuel crisis, Grant Shapps admits|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-petrol-shortage-grant-shapps-b1928368.html |access-date=6 October 2021|website=The Independent}}</ref><ref name="bbc-202107">{{cite news |title=How serious is the shortage of lorry drivers? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/57810729 |access-date=1 October 2021 |work=BBC News |date=14 July 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210929005239/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/57810729 |archive-date=29 September 2021|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Waterfield |first=Bruno |title=EU single market avoids supply problems |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/eu-single-market-avoids-supply-problems-petrol-lorry-drivers-ld5526lv6 |url-status=live |work=The Times |date=29 September 2021 |access-date=30 September 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210929042941/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/eu-single-market-avoids-supply-problems-petrol-lorry-drivers-ld5526lv6 |archive-date=29 September 2021}}</ref> In a July 2021 report, the [[Road Haulage Association]] estimated the UK faced a shortage of up to 100,000 truck drivers.<ref>{{cite web |date=July 2021 |title=A Report on the Driver Shortage |url=https://www.rha.uk.net/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=ICI0C-FWmVo%3D |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220531230607/https://www.rha.uk.net/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=ICI0C-FWmVo%3D |archive-date=31 May 2022 |archive-format=PDF |access-date=31 May 2022 |website=Road Haulage Association |format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=UK warned visa plan to fix truck driver shortage will not solve crunch |url=https://www.reuters.com/world/uk/uk-warned-visa-plan-fix-truck-driver-shortage-will-not-solve-crunch-2021-09-25/ |publisher=Reuters |date=26 September 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title='Brexit made clear Eastern Europeans are not welcome in UK' |url=https://www.dw.com/en/brexit-made-clear-eastern-europeans-are-not-welcome-in-uk/av-59410886 |work=Deutsche Welle |date=5 October 2021}}</ref>

Forecasts were made at the time of the referendum that Brexit would impose trade barriers, leading to a decline in trade between the United Kingdom and the European Union: however after a dip in 2020 as result of worldwide lockdowns, by 2022 trade in both directions had risen to higher levels than before Brexit.<ref>[https://view.officeapps.live.com/op/view.aspx?src=https%3A%2F%2Fassets.publishing.service.gov.uk%2Fgovernment%2Fuploads%2Fsystem%2Fuploads%2Fattachment_data%2Ffile%2F1129069%2Fuk-exports-and-imports-by-eu-and-non-eu-seasonally-adjusted-current-prices.ods&wdOrigin=BROWSELINK Total UK exports and imports (goods and services) by EU and non-EU, seasonally adjusted, current price] – UK trade in numbers: [[Office for National Statistics]]</ref>

==Cultural references==
{{main|Brexit in popular culture}}
Brexit has inspired many creative works, such as murals, sculptures, novels, plays, movies and video games. The response of British artists and writers to Brexit has in general been negative, reflecting a reported overwhelming percentage of people involved in Britain's [[creative industries]] voting against leaving the European Union.<ref>{{cite web |first=Mia |last=Jankowicz |title=Britain's thriving art scene strangled by Brexit chaos |work=Politics.co.uk |date=20 March 2017 |url=http://www.politics.co.uk/comment-analysis/2017/03/20/britain-s-thriving-art-scene-strangled-by-brexit-chaos |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180924114435/http://www.politics.co.uk/comment-analysis/2017/03/20/britain-s-thriving-art-scene-strangled-by-brexit-chaos |archive-date=24 September 2018}}</ref> Despite issues around immigration being central in the Brexit debate, British artists left the migrants' perspective largely unexplored. However, Brexit also inspired UK-based migrant artists to create new works and "claim agency over their representation within public spaces and create a platform for a new social imagination that can facilitate transnational and trans-local encounters, multicultural democratic spaces, sense of commonality, and solidarity."<ref>{{cite book |last=Lech |first=K. |date=2020 |chapter=Claiming Their Voice: Foreign Memories on the Post-Brexit Stage |editor-last1=Meerzon |editor-first1=Y. |editor-last2=Dean |editor-first2=D. |editor-last3=McNeil |editor-first3=D. |title=Migration and Stereotypes in Performance and Culture |series=Contemporary Performance InterActions |pages=215–234 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |doi=10.1007/978-3-030-39915-3_12 |isbn=978-3-030-39914-6 |s2cid=226721346 |chapter-url=https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-030-39915-3_12}}</ref>

